# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bomb-disposal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The regiment's history commences in the period immediately after World War II.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] At the time, the regional Commands HQs across the UK established Ammunition Inspectorates to oversee the drawdown of the vast stockpiles of ammunition in numerous sub depots across the country, much of it was still stocked alongside many of the roads in the countryside.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] These Command Ammunition Inspectorates, Northern Command, Southern Command etc. were eventually grouped into one unit, 1 Ammunition Inspection and Disposal Unit RAOC, which formed on 15 March 1972 at Salisbury.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] In April 1982, 1 Ammo IDU became 11 Ordnance Battalion (EOD) and was relocated to Didcot.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 5 April 1993, the battalion was retitled to 11 EOD Regiment RLC, following the formation of the RLC.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] In June 2018 the Regiment was renamed to 11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Regiment RLC, in recognition of the importance of Search within the Explosive Ordnance Disposal community.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The Regiment is based at Vauxhall Barracks, Didcot, Oxfordshire having moved there from Old Sarum in 1982.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] Due to its long and close association with the town, the Regiment was awarded the Freedom of Didcot on 17 September 2007 and were conferred "the honour and distinction of exercising all customary Regimental Privileges when parading in or marching through the Town of Didcot".
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The Regiment exercised its right to march through the town of Didcot on 22 September 2007, led by the Commanding Officer Lt Col RL Maybery QGM RLC.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 19 November 2010, in a ceremony at Didcot Parkway railway station, a High Speed Train locomotive, no.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] 43087 operated by Great Western Railway (FGW), was named *11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal Regiment Royal Logistic Corps*.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The ceremony was attended by Lt Col Gareth Bex (Commanding Officer); soldiers of the Regiment; Mark Hopwood, of FGW; Keith Mitchell, leader of the county council; and the MP for Wantage, Ed Vaizey.
[src:bomb-disposal/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 15 March 2018 the regiment was awarded the Firmin Sword of Peace, one of the highest accolades that can be bestowed upon a military unit.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] From April through June 1919, a series of bombings were carried out or attempted across the United States by Galleanists (followers of Italian insurrectionary anarchist Luigi Galleani).
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The targets included anti-immigration politicians, anti-anarchist officials, and prominent businessmen, as well as a journalist and a church.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Almost all of the bombs were sent by mail.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were one of the major factors contributing to the First Red Scare.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two people were killed, including one of the bombers, and two injured.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] In late April 1919, at least 36 booby trap dynamite-filled bombs were mailed to a cross-section of prominent politicians and appointees, including the Attorney General as well as justice officials, newspaper editors and businessmen, including John D.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The mail bombs were wrapped in brown paper with similar address and advertising labels.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Inside, wrapped in bright green paper and stamped "Gimbel Brothers-Novelty Samples", was a cardboard box with a 6 by 3 by 1 inch (150 by 80 by 30 mm) block of hollowed wood, packed with a stick of dynamite.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] A small vial of sulfuric acid was fastened to the wood block, along with three fulminate-of-mercury blasting caps.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Opening one end of the box (the end marked "open") released a coil spring that caused the acid to drip from its vial onto the blasting caps; the acid ate through the caps, igniting them and detonating the dynamite.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The Galleanists intended their bombs to be delivered on May Day.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Since 1890 and the Second International, May 1 had been celebrated as the international day of communist, anarchist and socialist revolutionary solidarity.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Seattle Mayor Ole Hanson, who had recently attained national prominence for opposing a general strike in Seattle, received one of the mailed package bombs, but it was opened by William Langer, a member of his office staff.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Langer opened the wrong end of the box and the bottle of acid dropped onto a table without detonation.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] He took the bomb to the local police, who notified the Post Service and other police agencies.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Hardwick, who had co-sponsored the Alien Anarchists Exclusion Act of 1918, received a similarly disguised bomb.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] It blew off the hands of his housekeeper when she attempted to open the package.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The senator's wife was also injured in the blast, which severely burned her face and neck and a piece of shrapnel cut her lip and loosened several of her teeth.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] News reports of the Hardwick bomb described its distinctive packaging and an alert post office employee in New York connected this to 16 similar packages which he had set aside a few days earlier for insufficient postage.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Another 12 bombs were eventually recovered before reaching their intended targets.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] On the evening of June 2, 1919, the Galleanists managed to detonate nine large bombs nearly simultaneously in eight cities.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] These bombs were much larger than those sent in April, using up to 25 pounds (11 kg) of dynamite and all were wrapped or packaged with heavy metal slugs designed to act as shrapnel.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Addressees included government officials who had endorsed anti-sedition laws and deportation of immigrants suspected of crimes or associated with illegal movements, as well as judges who had sentenced anarchists to prison.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, who had already been the recipient of a mail bomb in April, was again attacked in the new wave of violence.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Though not seriously injured, Palmer and his family were shaken by the blast and the house itself was largely demolished.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two near-casualties of the same bomb were Assistant Secretary of the Navy Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his wife Eleanor, then living across the street from Palmer.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] They had passed the house just minutes before the explosion and their residence was close enough that one of the bomber's body parts landed on their doorstep.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The flyer was later traced to a print shop operated by two anarchists, typesetter Andrea Salsedo and compositor Roberto Elia, who were both Galleanists according to the later memoirs of other members.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Salsedo died under suspicious circumstances (either by suicide or defenestration depending on the source) was and Elia refused an offer to cancel deportation proceedings if he would testify about his role in the Galleanist organization.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Unable to secure enough evidence for criminal trials, authorities continued to use the Anarchist Exclusion Act and related statutes to deport known Galleanists.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Fueled by labor unrest and the anarchist bombings, and then spurred on by Attorney General A.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Mitchell Palmer's attempt to suppress radical and non-radical labor organizations, the response to the bombings was characterized by exaggerated rhetoric, illegal search and seizures, unwarranted arrests and detentions and the deportation of several hundred suspected radicals and anarchists.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, twice targeted by anarchist bombs, organized the nationwide series of police actions known as the Palmer raids in November 1919 and January 1920.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Under suspicion of violating the Espionage Act, the Sedition Act and/or the Immigration Act of 1918, approximately 10,000 people were arrested, of whom 3,500 were held in detention.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Of those held in detention, 556 resident aliens were eventually deported.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were dramatized in the 2012 film *No God, No Master.* The bombing of the home of Palmer was also dramatized in the 2011 film *J.
[src:bomb-disposal/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The June Bombings and the "Plain Words" fliers were referenced in the video game *Arkham Origins* by Anarky, one of the game's antagonists.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Since 28 February 2026, the United States and Israel have been at war with Iran and its regional allies.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Hostilities broke out after US–Israeli airstrikes killed Iranian officials and Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] These attacks were launched amidst negotiations to reach a nuclear peace agreement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran fired back missiles and drones on Israel, US-aligned Arab countries, and US bases; the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait retaliated.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran blocked the Strait of Hormuz, which disrupted the global economy by causing a fuel crisis.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In January, the Iran government massacred thousands of civilians in a crackdown on protests.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In response, President Donald Trump initiated the largest US military buildup in the region since the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Israeli forces launched the war on Iran on February 28.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US provided many rationales for the war, including preventing Iran from developing a nuclear weapon, regime change, and taking Iran's oil and gas resources.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The attacks damaged military bases, government buildings, schools, hospitals, and heritage sites; it also inflicted civilian casualties.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In retaliation, Iran launched drones and ballistic missiles at Israel and Arab countries, including Bahrain, Jordan, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and the Kurdistan Region of Iraq (KRI).
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] At the same time, the Hezbollah–Israel conflict escalated into the 2026 Lebanon war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The secretary-general of the United Nations and several countries condemned the US–Israeli strikes; the UN Security Council passed a resolution condemning Iran's retaliatory strikes on Gulf states.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Critics, including legal and international relations experts, criticized the US-Israeli attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The war's economic impact includes the largest ever supply disruption of the global oil market, disruptions to the natural gas, fertilizer, aviation and tourism industries, as well as volatility in financial markets.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] As of 16 June 2026, the cost of the war to the US taxpayers was estimated at US$113.3 billion.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The parties agreed to a two-week ceasefire, beginning on 8 April.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] It came under strain after Israeli attacked Lebanon and Iran refused to re-open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] After the failure of the Islamabad Talks on April 12-13, the US imposed a naval blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] On 14 June, a memorandum to end the war was announced, and signed on 17 June by Trump at the Palace of Versailles, and by President Masoud Pezeshkian in Tehran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The dual blockade was lifted the next day, but tensions escalated.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] On 28 June, despite multiple clashes, the US and Iran agreed to cease their exchange of attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The war has been referred to by a number of names.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The initial strikes on Iran were codenamed Operation Epic Fury by the United States government, and Operation Roaring Lion by the Israeli government, in line with their codename of Operation Rising Lion for their strikes on Iran during the Twelve-Day War in June 2025.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran codenamed its response Operation True Promise IV, with the "Third Imposed War" being an existing, plain name among Iranian state media, referencing earlier confrontations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The war has also been referred to by some outlets as the "Third Gulf War" ("Gulf War III"), following the Gulf War from 1990 to 1991, and the Iraq War (2003–2011), which has also been referred to as the "Second Gulf War" ("Gulf War II").
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Due to the war starting during the month of Ramadan, it has been known as the "Ramadan War".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Media outlets that have used this name include Al Jazeera, *India Today*, the Institute of Contemporary Islamic Thought, the state media of Iran, such as the *Tehran Times*, as well as the state media of Houthi-controlled Yemen, such as the Saba News Agency.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] A US- and UK-backed coup d'état in 1953 deposed Iranian prime minister Mohammad Mosaddegh due to his nationalization of the oil industry, strengthening the rule of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel maintained ties with Iran as part of its alliance of the periphery strategy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Resentment of the Shah's deference to Western interests and his autocratic rule led to the 1979 revolution in which Pahlavi was overthrown and replaced by an Islamic republic.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran severed diplomatic ties with the US and Israel and held the American embassy staff hostage for over a year.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] During the Iran–Iraq War, the US supported Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In 1988, a US warship struck an Iranian mine, and the US responded by attacking Iran's navy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] A few months later, the US mistakenly shot down a civilian Iranian flight.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran started a ballistic missile program to deter Iraqi missile attacks on Iranian cities and to compensate for its lack of a modern air force due to sanctions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Starting in the 1980s, Iran began engaging in proxy conflicts throughout the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran backed Hezbollah in Lebanon against Israel during and after the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] During the Iraq War, Iran supported militias fighting the US in Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Along with the Houthis in Yemen and other groups in Syria and Palestine, these proxy groups became part of the informal 'Axis of Resistance' committed to countering American, Israeli, Saudi, and Emirati influence in the region.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2002, Iran's covert nuclear program was first revealed, and Iran denied seeking a weapon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2003, Iran's AMAD Project was suspended following Ali Khamenei's fatwa against nuclear weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In 2005, the US began imposing sanctions targeting Iran's nuclear program, and in 2006 the United Nations Security Council (UNSC) imposed a series of sanctions against Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Israel conducted a campaign of cyberwarfare against Iranian nuclear facilities to disrupt their operations, while Israel assassinated several top Iranian nuclear scientists.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The UNSC concerns about Iran's nuclear program from 2006 led to the multilateral Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) between Iran and the US in 2015.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In January 2020, President Trump ordered the assassination of Qasem Soleimani, the commander of the Quds Force.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Following the October 7 attacks on Israel and the start of the Gaza war, tensions further escalated with Israel fighting Iran-backed militias across the Middle East, including Hamas, Hezbollah, and the Houthis.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Israeli strikes on the Iranian consulate in Damascus and the assassination of Ismail Haniyeh in 2024 were met with Iranian strikes on Israel in April and October.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In June 2025, Israel launched the Twelve-Day War by attacking Iranian military and nuclear facilities, provoking Iranian counter-strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US also struck Iranian nuclear facilities during the Twelve-Day War, which ended in a ceasefire.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] In early 2026, Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu lobbied President Donald Trump for a joint military strike on Iran, specifically targeting its leadership.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Following high-level meetings in February, Trump authorized "Operation Epic Fury", with reports citing Israeli intelligence provided by Netanyahu as a decisive factor in the decision.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran has long denied seeking nuclear weapons, saying its enrichment efforts were to generate nuclear power for civilian use.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Despite Iran's compliance with the JCPOA, Trump withdrew the US from the deal in 2018, re-imposed sanctions, and adopted a "maximum pressure" strategy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The Biden administration kept most of these sanctions, further damaging Iran's economy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Trump continued the "maximum pressure" approach in his second term.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent labelled the collapse of the Iranian currency in December 2025 as the strategy's "grand culmination".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] At his State of the Union Address in February 2026, Trump claimed Iran had restarted its nuclear program and was developing missiles capable of striking the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Trump's claims contradicted his previous claims that Iran's nuclear program was "obliterated" and US intelligence reports that Iran did not pose any threat towards the US, and needed until 2035 to build such missiles to do so.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] On 12 June 2025, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) found Iran non-compliant with its NPT safeguards agreement for the first time since 2005.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] A few days later, it was reported that Iran had stored highly enriched uranium in an underground facility that was undamaged by US bombings in 2025.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Subsequently, Iran denied the IAEA access to nuclear facilities that had been bombed, but did provide access to all unaffected facilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Analysts in the UK and US characterized Iran's strategy as nuclear hedging, developing the technical infrastructure to assemble a weapon on short notice while stopping short of production.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The *Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists* said that Iran was using its enrichment program and uranium stockpiles for leverage in international negotiations, and was willing to dilute or export its higher-level enriched uranium in exchange for sanctions relief and prevention of attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel is widely believed to possess nuclear weapons, with a stockpile estimated between 90 and 400 nuclear warheads.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Israel is the only nuclear-armed country that does not officially acknowledge its nuclear weapons capability.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Some scholars have argued that Israel's nuclear weapons have incentivized Iran to develop its own nuclear program, seen as maintaining a balance of nuclear deterrence, or causing a regional nuclear arms race.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Citing security threats, Israel rejects international calls to accede to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons or to participate in negotiations of a Middle East nuclear weapon free zone.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] This has frustrated both US and UK diplomatic efforts on such a zone.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Scholars also suggest US tacit acceptance of the Israeli nuclear weapons capability is seen as a double standard that undermines its diplomatic credibility in Middle East nonproliferation negotiations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Tensions between Iran and the United States during negotiations over Iran's nuclear program began to intensify in January 2026 amid Iran's massacres of its civilians in the crackdown of the 2025–2026 anti-government protests.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US and Iran restarted indirect talks in February, and agreed to meet in Switzerland to finalize the Islamabad Memorandum.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US began amassing air and naval assets in the region at a level not seen since the outset of the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq, including a pair of carrier strike groups and hundreds of aircraft at bases in the area.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The US administration accused Iran of building up its nuclear and missile programs to threaten the United States and its interests.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Iran in turn accused the US of waging "disinformation and misinformation" campaigns against it.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] The Council on American–Islamic Relations accused Trump of manufacturing justifications for war similar to those for the Iraq War while *Qatar Tribune* asserted that the administration was falsely claiming that WMDs were being built in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Regional actors, including Qatar, cautioned that any escalation could have severe consequences for the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p01] Negotiations regarding the Iranian nuclear program were held in February, and on 28 February 2026 the US and Israel conducted military strikes in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] IRST), Trump, traveling on Air Force One to Texas, authorized Operation Epic Fury.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] US missiles, drones, and Israeli fighter jets began striking Iran the next day, around 9:45 a.m.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The strikes took place during negotiations over Iran's nuclear program, and coincided with the holy month of Ramadan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The operation was codenamed Operation Roaring Lion by Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Israeli Air Force (IAF) said it struck 500 military targets in Iran in the largest combat sortie in its history.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian naval vessels were also targeted.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it used over 1,200 bombs in 24 hours.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] US strikes were carried out by planes based around the Middle East and from aircraft carriers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran's supreme leader Ali Khamenei and thousands of Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) personnel, were killed as military bases were attacked.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Strikes hit Tehran's Pasteur Street district, where the presidential palace is, and the National Security Council.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The strikes were coupled with cyberattacks on Iranian infrastructure, media, and phone apps, with messages calling on Iranians to rise up against their government.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The cyberattacks resulted in a near-total internet blackout in Iran, lasting over 60 hours with connectivity dropping to as low as 1% of normal levels, disrupting government communications, state media, and public services.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran restricted internet access, allowing access only to government-approved users until 26 May.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli officials said months-long planning preceded the strikes, allowing them to pinpoint targets, attain "tactical surprise", and gain US support.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Attacking during the morning, rather than at night when most of Israel's previous attacks on Iran took place, added to the element of surprise.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel declared a state of emergency, citing expectation of Iranian retaliation, and warned its citizens to remain in protected areas.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel called up 20,000 reservists in addition to the 50,000 on duty.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Israeli Ministry of Health moved its hospital operations underground.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 28 February, Trump released a statement saying the purpose of the strikes was regime change.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump said Iran's "menacing activities" endangered the US and its allies.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] He cited the Iran hostage crisis, support for non-state actors such as Hamas and Hezbollah, and its killings of protesters.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump cited Iran calling "Death to America" and its alleged history of attacking US civilians and soldiers as evidence of Iran's intent against the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump and Benjamin Netanyahu warned of the potential threat of nuclear weapons in Iran and called on Iranians to overthrow their government.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli defense minister Israel Katz labeled the strikes a "pre-emptive attack" intended to "remove threats to...Israel".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran rejected claims that it intended to attack the US, citing the aggressive posture of the US military as evidence.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran reacted within hours by launching missiles and drones.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran codenamed its response Operation True Promise IV, and state media dubbed the events the Ramadan War.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran struck Israeli targets in Tel Aviv and Haifa as well as countries throughout the Persian Gulf.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Targets included Bahrain's capital Manama, Kuwait International Airport, the United Arab Emirates' capital Abu Dhabi, Riyadh and Eastern Province in Saudi Arabia, and Erbil International Airport and the US Consulate General in Erbil in Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran reported striking the US bases of Al Udeid Air Base in Qatar, Ali Al Salem Air Base in Kuwait, Al Dhafra Air Base in the UAE, and the US Fifth Fleet headquarters in Bahrain.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 1 or 2 March, Iran struck the radar bases for US THAAD missile defense systems in Jordan, the UAE and Saudi Arabia, destroying at least one.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 1 March, Iran launched more strikes, including missiles and drones on Bahrain, Israel, Jordan, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The UK reported "missiles fired in the direction of Cyprus", but "don't believe they were targeted at Cyprus".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] However, the presidents of Cyprus and Northern Cyprus contradicted the claims that any missiles were fired at Cyprus.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Palau-flagged *Skylight* and Marshall Islands-flagged *MKD VYOM* tankers were targeted off Oman's coast.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Shipping through the Strait of Hormuz slowed to a standstill, with 150 freight ships, including oil tankers, stalled.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] To avert further Iranian strikes, the E3-the UK, France, and Germany- resolved to back "proportionate military defensive measures" against drones and ballistic missiles, signaling the potential for direct involvement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] British prime minister Keir Starmer said the US could use British bases for "defensive" strikes on Iran and disclosed that Ukrainian and other specialists would aid Gulf efforts to foil Iranian drone strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Saudi Crown Prince Salman, with US backing, vowed to employ military force against Iranian incursions, calling Iranian strikes "cowardly" due to Saudi airspace being closed to US and Israeli attackers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump announced that the US had accepted an Iranian proposal to negotiations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump issued letters to Congress leaders according to the 1973 War Powers Resolution.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 2 March, the US embassy in Kuwait was struck and closed indefinitely.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US-flagged tanker *Stena Imperative* and the Honduras-flagged tanker *Athe Nova* were struck.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An advisor to an IRGC commander said he would set fire to any ship coming through the Strait of Hormuz, and added that no oil will leave the area.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Qatar shot down two Iranian Su-24 bombers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Qatari Ministry of Defense announced that Ras Laffan Industrial City, the main Qatari gas facility, and Mesaieed Industrial Area were struck by Iranian drones.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] According to satellite imagery analysis by the Energy Economics and Society Research Institute, Ras Laffan appeared to not have been damaged before the "unprecedented shutdown" which sent fuel prices higher.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US and Israel attacked the Natanz Nuclear Facility and the Iranian media reported damage to the Khatam-al-Anbia and Gandhi hospitals.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In a friendly fire incident, the pilot of an F/A-18 of the Kuwait Air Force shot down three US F-15E fighters.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Hezbollah began firing rockets and missiles on Israel in retaliation for the killing of Khamenei.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Hezbollah claimed that the attack was a "defensive act" after more than a year of Israeli attacks despite a 2024 truce.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] It added that it restarted fighting to force Israel to stop its aggression and evacuate from seized Lebanese territories, emphasizing that the move was unrelated to the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Lebanon banned military activities by Hezbollah after the attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An IDF spokesperson stated the attack was "an official declaration of war by Hezbollah", vowing to "neutralize" the threat.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel struck southern Lebanon, Beirut, and the Beqaa Valley, with the IDF saying it had killed the head of Hezbollah's intelligence Hussein Makled and Adham Adnan al-Othman, the head of Palestinian Islamic Jihad's armed wing, the Al-Quds Brigades.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Royal Air Force station at Akrotiri, Cyprus, was targeted by a drone strike causing damage to a runway.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Another strike on Cyprus led to Greece announcing that it would deploy frigates and F-16s to defend Cyprus from strikes by Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The pro-Iran militant group Iraqi Guardians of Blood Brigades claimed responsibility for attacks on the US Victory Base near Baghdad International Airport and Erbil in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Islamic Resistance in Iraq claimed responsibility for 23 drone strikes on US assets in Erbil.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 3 March, US and Israeli strikes destroyed the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC) headquarters, the Expediency Discernment Council building in Tehran, and what Israeli officials described as an alleged underground nuclear weapons facility called Min Zadai.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The proximity of these strikes to the Bushehr Nuclear Power Plant (about 12 km (7.5 mi) away) prompted the Russian agency Rosatom to suspend construction on new units and evacuate non-essential staff.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] US officials said its forces had severely damaged Iran's naval capabilities, mainly in the Gulf of Oman, where several Iranian warships were destroyed and key bases hit.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Debris from an airstrike damaged Golestan Palace, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, causing UNESCO to issue a statement that damaging UNESCO sites is against international law.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel Katz authorized a ground invasion of Lebanon on 3 March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] This incursion in southern Lebanon was with forces from the 91st Division with the goal to establish a "security layer" for the Israeli residents of northern settlements against Hezbollah, expecting to destroy their infrastructure in the Israel-Lebanon border.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Lebanese government reported that such Israeli preventive attacks reached Kfarkela and Qouzah, leading the Lebanese army to redeploy from newly established border posts amid escalating Israeli activity in violation of the 2024 Israel–Lebanon ceasefire agreement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reported that it killed Daoud Alizadeh, the commander of the Quds Force's Lebanon branch, in Tehran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Western diplomats said Qatar had struck Iran after Iran had attempted to strike Doha's airport and Qatar shot down two Iranian Su-24 bombers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Qatar denied the accusation that it had joined the "campaign targeting Iran".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran warned it would hit all economic hubs in the Middle East, and any defensive European military involvement would be considered an act of war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 4 March, US secretary of state Marco Rubio announced that the US-Israeli attacks on Iran would increase in intensity.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel attacks hit the Basij headquarters.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The IDF announced that an F-35I "Adir" shot down a Russian-made Iranian Yak-130 fighter jet over Tehran, the first time that an F-35 has shot down a crewed fighter jet in air-to-air combat, and the first time the Israeli Air Force shot down an aircraft since 1985.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran launched strikes against the Al Udeid Air Base, and Aramco's Ras Tanura oil refining facility.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US ordered the evacuation of non-essential workers in Cyprus in anticipation of Iranian strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A ballistic missile launched from Iran was intercepted by NATO air defense systems as it entered Turkish airspace, marking an escalation in the conflict.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Turkey asserted its right to self-defense after the missile landed in Dörtyol, Hatay Province, and NATO secretary general Mark Rutte stated that the alliance was committed to defending Turkey.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian frigate, IRIS *Dena*, was sunk in the Indian Ocean by United States Navy submarine USS *Charlotte*, about 40 nautical miles (74 km; 46 mi) south of Galle, Sri Lanka.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The vessel was returning to Iran following its participation in the International Fleet Review 2026 and the multilateral Exercise MILAN at Visakhapatnam, India.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The exercise required ships not to carry ammunition, and the US likely knew the *Dena* was defenseless, since it sent a maritime patrol aircraft to participate.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] It was the first ship sunk by a submarine in active combat since the Falklands War, and the first by an American submarine since World War II.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The government of Azerbaijan said on 5 March that drones from Iran struck Azerbaijan's Nakhchivan exclave damaging an airport and injuring two civilians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Keir Starmer confirmed UK's bases on Cyprus would be used to defend the airspace of Jordan from Iranian drones, while Italy, the Netherlands and Spain confirmed they would send warships to defend Cyprus.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Ireland stated it was willing to protect Cyprus and join the European defense coalition mobilized around the island if requested.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The IDF killed Hamas official Wassim Attallah al-Ali in Beddawi, Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump said on 6 March that there are "no time limits" for how long the war will continue.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Iranian tanker IRIS *Bushehr* was interned by the Sri Lanka Navy, marking the first instance of a warship being interned in a neutral country since World War II.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 7 March, the US sent a third aircraft carrier, USS *George H.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The British aircraft carrier HMS *Prince of Wales* was placed on advanced readiness to defend British interests in the region.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 7 March, Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian apologized for strikes on neighboring countries, citing "miscommunication in the ranks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] He stated those countries would not be targeted unless the US launched attacks from them; however, Iranian attacks continued, highlighting limited control over the Revolutionary Guard chief Ahmad Vahidi.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 8 March, Khamenei's second son, Mojtaba, was designated as Iran's new supreme leader.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israeli airstrikes hit Iranian oil storage facilities, killing four people.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Strikes on fuel depots near Tehran caused a "river of fire" to pour out along the streets, and the city became engulfed in thick black smoke, causing toxic acidic rain to fall in the surrounding area.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Residents were advised by Iranian authorities to stay indoors, wear masks when outside, and conserve food and fuel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Kuwait reported that two of its officers were killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Saudi Civil Defense agency said that a strike on a compound in Al-Kharj killed two people.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] US Central Command announced the death of a seventh US service member from an Iranian attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The UK confirmed its forces had intercepted an Iranian drone headed towards Iraq, and declared its intention to send a Merlin helicopter to the region to detect aerial threats.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] According to the Iranian Red Crescent Society, 65 schools and 32 medical facilities had been targeted, and more than 10,000 civilian sites damaged.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 9 March, NATO confirmed the interception of a second ballistic missile in Turkish airspace.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Turkey deployed six F-16s and air defence systems to Northern Cyprus.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump claimed that "the war is very complete, pretty much", after speaking with Russian president Putin, and said "we already won the war in many ways." He claimed that the Strait of Hormuz was open and expressed interest in taking it over from Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump went back on some comments during a press conference later that day, supporting Defense Secretary Hegseth in stating that the war was just the "beginning of building a new country" and it would end "soon".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Following Syrian president Ahmed al-Sharaa's support for the Lebanon's objective to disarm Hezbollah, the group targeted the city of Inkhil in Syria.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] About a dozen B-1B bombers arrived at bases in Europe.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] GPS jamming of uncertain origin disrupted navigation of ships near the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The United States Department of State designated the Muslim Brotherhood branch in Sudan as a terrorist organization.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 10 March, an IRGC commander stated that Iran was only firing missiles with payloads of 1,000 kg or more.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] AFP reported that Iran's attacks were the "most intense and heaviest" since the start of the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] This showed a shift in tactics from saturating air defences to high-impact penetration strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] American general Dan Caine acknowledged that Iran was fighting back, but not harder than the US expected.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Following the Syrian presidency's support for the disarmament of Hezbollah and a campaign of mobilization by the Syrian army on the Lebanese border, shells from Lebanon landed in Serghaya, 20 km (12 mi) from Damascus where the Syrian Armed Forces forces presided.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel issued an urgent evacuation notice to southern suburbs of Beirut.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Defense analyst AJ Jaff reported that Iran's ballistic missile launch rate fell 92% from day one of the war (480 to 40) and the drone launch rate fell 92% (720 to 60).
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 11 March 14 US bombers were deployed to RAF Fairford in the UK, where bombs were being prepared for loading.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] This followed US war secretary Hegseth's statement that it was the "most intense day of strikes inside Iran".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reportedly struck the Parchin military complex.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A branch of Bank Sepah in Tehran was hit by a strike, prompting the IRGC to warn that they could retaliate by striking US or Israeli banks in the region.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran hit Stryker, a US-based medical supply company with a cyberattack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 12 March, UNICEF reported that 300 children had been killed, thousands injured, hundreds of thousands displaced, and millions unable to attend schools due to the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian deputy intelligence minister Akbar Ghaffari was killed in an airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian attack set two tankers on fire off the Iraqi coast, killing one person.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The historical Safavid-era building of Rashk-e Jenan, was destroyed by US-Israeli strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Other buildings damaged included the Chehel Sotoun pavilion, Rakib Khaneh Mansion, Timurid Hall, Ashraf Hall and the Ali Qapu palace.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Many affected buildings and monuments were legally protected by the Blue Shield International, which called damaging them a war crime.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] French soldiers were injured in a drone strike at a base in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] French president Emmanuel Macron announced on 13 March that a soldier was killed in the attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 13 March, to help deal with the economic costs of the war, the US temporarily lifted restrictions on the sale of Russian oil.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran announced a coordinated offensive by its navy, army, and Hezbollah against Israel and US bases.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel reported that 58 people have been hospitalized due to injuries following a missile strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Kuwait authorities stated that defense equipment and the country's main airport were attacked, and power lines gone out of service.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Missiles entered Turkish air space and were intercepted, with explosions heard near Adana.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel struck IRGC checkpoints after receiving tip-offs by on the ground informants.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Reuters reported Israel had struck positions of the Basij used to suppress Iranian protests.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] As of the third week, analysts found little evidence of significant defections in the Iranian military, which have been considered a necessary condition for regime change.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US conducted an attack on Kharg Island, a key oil export hub home to 90 percent of Iran's oil exports.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Over 90 military sites were targeted while the oil infrastructure was not targeted "for reasons of decency", according to Trump.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 14 March, Kata'ib Hezbollah security commander Abu Ali al-Askari was killed in an airstrike in Baghdad.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Royal Tulip Al Rasheed Hotel in Baghdad's Green Zone was hit by a drone whilst hosting an EU and Saudi Arabian delegation.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The attack was not claimed by anyone; however, due to the proximity of a similar attack 48 hours earlier on the US embassy in Baghdad, there were suspicions it was an Iranian attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 16 March, China and US-aligned NATO nations in Europe rejected Trump's call to provide military support to reopen the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump rebuked his NATO allies, calling their decision a "very foolish mistake".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day, White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt stated that the Trump administration will not rule out a military draft for the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] While doing so, she clarified that a draft is not "part of the current plan," but that the president is open to any suggestions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 17 March, Trump made a statement on Truth Social renouncing NATO's assistance, and unexpectedly, US allies in the Indo-Pacific, namely Japan, South Korea, and Australia, for refusing to join US-led attacks on Iran during the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump declared that the United States "[does] not need the help of anyone" regarding the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In the morning of 17 March, senior Iranian officials, including Ali Larijani and Basij chief Gholamreza Soleimani were targeted by Israeli airstrikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Both their deaths were later confirmed by Iranian state media.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran launched a missile barrage that killed two Israeli civilians in Ramat Gan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, Israel launched a ground invasion of southern Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 18 March, Israel struck the South Pars natural gas field in the Persian Gulf and its neighboring refineries in Iran with US coordination.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In retaliation, Iran attacked the world's largest LNG production facility in Qatar.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump claimed he was unaware of the South Pars attack, promised that there would be no more Israeli attacks on Iranian oil infrastructure, and threatened Iran not to continue attacking Qatari energy infrastructure.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it had killed Iranian intelligence minister Esmaeil Khatib in an overnight airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A hair salon in Beit Awwa was struck by a projectile, killing four women, with Israeli authorities stating that it was most likely cluster munitions and Palestinian authorities saying it was an errant Israeli interceptor.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 19 March, a US F-35 made an emergency landing after a suspected hit by Iranian forces.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A BAZAN Group refinery in Haifa was hit during a broader Iranian missile attack on the area as a retaliation for Israeli attacks on South Pars gas facilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Netanyahu insisted that "You can't make a revolution from the air" and that "there must be a ground component—I won't share with you all the options", implying that there was a potential for limited assault operations involving soldiers on the ground in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US began an aerial campaign against Iranian vessels and drones in the Strait of Hormuz in an effort to reopen it to international shipping.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Admiral Brad Cooper said that the US military had so far struck more than 8,000 Iranian military targets, including 130 vessels.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 21 March, the US conducted strikes on the Natanz Nuclear Facility using bunker buster bombs to target the site.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Russia condemned the strikes on Natanz as a "blatant violation of international law," while the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) urged military restraint "to avoid any risk of a nuclear accident".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran struck the southern Israeli town of Dimona, injuring at least 78 people.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran said that it targeted the Shimon Peres Negev Nuclear Research Center.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Citing unnamed US officials, CNN and *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Iran unsuccessfully attempted to strike the joint US–UK military base at Diego Garcia on the Chagos Islands in the British Indian Ocean Territory.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The report said one of the missiles broke apart mid-flight, while another was intercepted by a SM-3 air defence missile launched by a US warship.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said that Iran used a two-stage intercontinental ballistic missile to target the island.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied launching missiles towards Diego Garcia, saying that it was an Israeli false flag attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response the UK Foreign Secretary confirmed and denounced the Iranian attack on their end, and additionally expanded permission for the United States to bomb certain targets using their bases.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] No evidence has been presented that the alleged Iranian missiles neared Diego Garcia or that one was intercepted.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthi movement in Yemen warned that it would respond to any escalation against Iran, including efforts to reopen the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] It specifically warned the two Arab countries offering to join the Strait of Hormuz campaign—Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates—that they "will be the first to lose in this battle".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis further threatened to join the war in the event that US allies joined the attack on Iran or if the US and Israel used the Red Sea to carry out operations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Lebanon's government expelled the Iranian ambassador.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Trump issued an ultimatum to Iran, threatening to strike its power plants unless it opened the Strait of Hormuz within 48 hours.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran doubled down, threatening to "completely" close the Strait of Hormuz and strike vital infrastructure across the region such as energy and desalination facilities critical for drinking water.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied the talks ever took place or were taking place and called the president "deceitful".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran rejected the 15-point peace plan presented by the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran asserted that Lebanon must be included as part of a ceasefire deal, thereby making a ceasefire conditional on an end to the 2026 Lebanon war against Hezbollah.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 24 March, Israel or its allies shot down an Iranian missile crossing above Lebanon at high altitude, according to the Lebanese army, which also confirmed that the missile was not targeting Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] This was the first time during the current conflict when a shootdown of an Iranian missile took place over Lebanese territory.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A US strike on the Habbaniya military base—which hosts units from the Popular Mobilization Forces—in Al Anbar Governorate killed seven members of the Iraqi Armed Forces and injured 13 others.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iraqi prime minister Mohammed Shia' al-Sudani summoned the US embassy's chargé d'affaires in Baghdad.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iranian state media threatened that Iran could seize Bahraini and Emirati territory if the US "makes any mistakes", while signaling its readiness to open a new front in Yemen by closing the Bab al-Mandab Strait together with the Houthis.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Israel said it killed Iran's top naval commander, Alireza Tangsiri, purportedly as part of an effort to reopen the Strait of Hormuz, which Katz said Tangsiri was "directly responsible" for the closure of.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 27 March, a day after Trump and Hegseth announced the "neutralization" of Iran's military, an Iranian missile and drone strike on Prince Sultan Air Base damaged several US refueling aircraft and injured at least 15 US soldiers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An E-3 Sentry was also damaged by the strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Military analyst Cedric Leighton described the attack as a "a serious blow to [US] surveillance capabilities".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, Iran blocked two Chinese ships from entering the strait and sought to formalize fees for ships passing through it.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Despite pushes for talks, Israeli defense minister Israel Katz publicly vowed to "intensify and expand" Israeli attacks in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The same day, the Shahid Khondab Heavy Water Complex in Arak—which has in the past been used to test uranium enrichment—and the Ardakan yellowcake production plant in Yazd Province were confirmed to have been damaged in Israeli airstrikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis joined the war on 28 March launching a ballistic missile towards Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis said that they had launched ballistic missiles targeting "sensitive" military sites in Israel, and vowed to continue the attacks "until the aggression on all resistance fronts stops".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The missile was intercepted and no casualties were reported.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The Houthis subsequently launched a second missile at Eilat.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, the internationally recognized Yemeni government condemned Iran's "frequent attempts to drag Yemen" into conflict "through its terrorist militias".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day, 2,500 US marines from the 31st Marine Expeditionary Unit arrived in the Middle East, expected to be part of US efforts to open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] US Central Command (CENTCOM) stated that it had struck over 11,000 targets in Iran since the beginning of the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 28 March, joint US–Israeli airstrikes severely damaged several residential and civilian facilities, including the Iran University of Science and Technology.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] In response, Iran threatened to attack Israeli and American colleges across the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Airstrikes also struck a 10,000-cubic-meter water reservoir in Haftkel, in Khuzestan province.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] An Iranian missile struck a chemical plant in the Ne'ot Hovav industrial zone, injuring one person and causing fears of a hazardous leak.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] A convoy of the Iraqi Popular Mobilization Forces was seen entering Khorramshahr in southwestern Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Eleven-year-old child soldier Alireza Jafari died following an Israeli drone strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 29 March, Trump stated that he would prefer to "take the oil in Iran".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] He proposed taking Iran's oil export center, Kharg Island, claiming that the United States could capture the territory "very easily", and implying that the US could occupy it for some time.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On 30 March, Trump said that if a deal were not reached soon and the Strait of Hormuz reopened, the US would strike all of Iran's power plants, oil wells, Kharg Island, and possibly all its desalinization plants, although the feasibility and strategic value of some of Trump's threats were contested.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] On the same day Turkey and NATO intercepted the fourth missile directed towards Turkish territory.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] Iran denied firing a missile at Turkey, claiming that it was a false flag attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US began flying B-52 bombers over Iranian territory for the first time, indicating its confidence of air supremacy over Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] The US used bombers to target an ammunition depot and air base in Isfahan, causing large explosions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] U.S-allied Gulf states such as Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait, and Bahrain reportedly pushed Trump to continue the war until there are significant changes in Iran's leadership.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p02] American journalist Shelly Kittleson was kidnapped in Baghdad by Kata'ib Hezbollah—the strongest faction within the PMF—who demanded that the Iraqi government release several detained members of the group.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 April, Mehr News Agency, a semi-official Iranian government news outlet, reported that policy expert and former foreign minister Kamal Kharazi was seriously injured and his wife was killed in an airstrike which hit his home.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian officials described the attack as an attempt to derail diplomacy, noting that Kharazi was overseeing a possible meeting between Iranian officials and US vice president JD Vance.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Airstrikes on the strategically important Hengam Island in the Strait of Hormuz caused seven injuries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Netanyahu asserted that the US–Israeli strikes have eliminated Iran's ability to produce nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles, thereby removing "two existential threats" to Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 April, two US strikes on the B1 bridge between Tehran and Karaj, which was described as the highest bridge in the Middle East, reportedly killed eight people and wounded 95 others, causing it to collapse.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Experts assessed the attack as a possible war crime; it was celebrated by Trump.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] At the time of the attack, many Iranian families had been gathered in the parks below the bridge to celebrate Sizdah Be-dar.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran revealed major damage to the century-old medical center Pasteur Institute of Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US defense secretary Hegseth boasted of "death and destruction from the sky all day long".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The IDF also announced that one of its strikes in the Kermanshah area of Iran killed Iranian ballistics missile chief Makram Atimi and several battalion commanders from Atimi's central Iranian ballistic missile unit.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An Iranian ballistic missile strike damaged an Israeli drone factory in Petah Tikva.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran's army chief, Amir Hatami, stated that if US forces invade the country, "not a single person" among the invaders will survive.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 April, Iranian forces shot down a US Air Force F-15E Strike Eagle fighter jet over the country, with the wreckage falling in the Kohgiluyeh and Boyer-Ahmad province of Iran, prompting a search and rescue mission by US helicopters.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The pilot was rescued that same day, but the WSO remained missing and was rescued alive 48 hours later.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] A US A-10 "Warthog" aircraft was downed and its single crew member ejected near the Strait of Hormuz and was rescued.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran released a video showing shooting down the aircraft using surface-to-air missile.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Tehran's Shahid Beheshti University was hit by airstrikes, making the total number of universities hit to more than 30, according to the Iranian Minister of Science.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 April, explosions were reported at an auxiliary building of the Bushehr Nuclear Power Plant as well as the Mahshahr Special Petrochemical Zone in Mahshahr, Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The airstrikes in Mahshahr killed at least five and injured 170 others.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An Iranian missile strike hit in the vicinity of the IDF's HaKirya headquarters in Tel Aviv.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 April, the IRGC announced that the head of the IRGC's intelligence organisation, Major General Majid Khademi, had been killed in a joint US-Israeli airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Their statement claimed that Khademi had "played a major role in Iran's intelligence and security apparatus over nearly five decades".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that Yazdan Mir, a high-ranking commander of the IRGC Quds Force, had also been killed in the attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, before Trump's deadline for targeting Iranian infrastructure, Israel carried out strikes on the South Pars Petrochemical facility in Asaluyeh, Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Israeli Air Force said that "85% of Iran's petrochemical exports" had been taken offline by now.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] At least 34 people, including six children, were killed in US-Israeli airstrikes across Iran, including against Sharif University of Technology and residential areas.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian vice president and reformist politician Mohammad Reza Aref, who is also an alumnus of the university, described the alleged use of a bunker-buster bomb as a "symbol of Trump's madness and ignorance".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 April, The Rafi'-Nia synagogue in central Tehran was destroyed in an airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that the building was destroyed due to collateral damage and that it was never meant to be the direct target of the airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, US forces began strikes on Kharg Island.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran said its restraint in targeting oil infrastructure in the region would no longer apply.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump posted to Truth Social that "a whole civilization will die tonight, never to be brought back again", causing international concern that Trump would use nuclear weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Secretary General of Amnesty International said that Trump's statement "may constitute a threat to commit genocide".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Multiple right-wing commentators and many Democrats condemned the post, and some called for him to be removed through the 25th Amendment.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The White House denied considering using nuclear weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The White House later said that "only the president knows" what he would do on Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 April Trump announced that the US and Iran had reached an agreement based on the 10-point proposal mediated by Pakistani prime minister Shehbaz Sharif and Field Marshal Asim Munir.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US, Israel, and Iran agreed to a two-week ceasefire, under which Iran would re-open the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] After the announcement, Iran's Lavan Island oil refinery and Sirri Island crude export facilities were struck; no party claimed responsibility.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran continued missile and drone strikes on Gulf Arab states.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The refinery attack was later revealed to have been done secretly by the UAE.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel and the US asserted that the ceasefire did not include Lebanon, contradicting the Pakistani mediators and Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah said it had halted attacks on Israel and on Israeli soldiers in Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite the ceasefire, Israel launched "Operation Eternal Darkness", which included targeting all Hezbollah's command and control centers in southern Lebanon, Beirut and the Beqaa Valley.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] These were the largest attacks since the start of the war, killing at least 357 people and injuring more than 1,200.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In Beirut alone, 92 people were killed and at least 740 injured.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In response, Iran threatened to attack Israel "if the aggressions against dear Lebanon are not brought to an immediate end", Iran paused Hormuz traffic over Israeli attacks in Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah claimed responsibility for launching rockets towards northern Israel as a response to "ceasefire violations".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 11 April, Trump said that American forces had started "clearing" the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran claimed that an American ship on its way to the strait turned back after being warned.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Wall Street Journal* reported US Navy destroyers entered the strait for the first time since the war began.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian government reportedly threatened to attack the ships, accusing the US of a ceasefire violation.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US Central Command said the ships are taking part in minesweeping.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump declared that the US Navy would begin its blockade of "all Ships trying to enter, or leave, the Strait of Hormuz" from 13 April.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] He said the US Navy would stop any ships that paid tolls to Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] However, United States Central Command clarified that the blockade would only be enforced on ships travelling to or from Iranian ports.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The IRGC Navy said any military vessel approaching the strait would be considered a ceasefire violation and meet a "severe response." Trump threatened to strike fast-attack ships of the IRGC Navy, similar to US strikes on drug traffickers during Operation Southern Spear.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran had 13 days of oil storage capacity, forcing it to shut down its oil fields and potentially damaging them.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An analyst estimated loss of import and export capacity would be US$435 million per day.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 14 April, four Iranian-linked ships traveled through the strait, despite the US blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] They later stopped or turned around, after presumed interception by the US Navy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Tankers leaving Chabahar Port were contacted by a US destroyer, while Boeing P-8 Poseidon aircraft were also used to intercept tankers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 16 April, Trump announced that Israel and Lebanon agreed to a ten-day truce.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran announced that passage of commercial vessels through the strait would be allowed during the truce.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite this, Trump said that the blockade would continue, so Iran announced it would reimpose restrictions on the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US stated that its blockade had intercepted 23 ships.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 19 April, Trump sent negotiators to Pakistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] He threatened that Iran would be "blown up" if the negotiations failed, saying the US will target power plants and bridges.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US Navy seized an Iranian cargo ship on 19 April, saying it was attempting to evade the blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran called this a breach of the ceasefire due to end on 22 April.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran retaliated by launching drones at US ships, though no damage was reported.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 21 April, the Pentagon said US soldiers boarded a tanker in the Indo-Pacific region to disrupt ships providing support to Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said the US military intercepted a "gift from China" to Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] China stated that it "opposes any malicious association".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Hours before the ceasefire was due to end, Trump extended it, saying he did so at Pakistan's request, to allow time for an Iranian proposal.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Hours afterwards, the IRGC announced that it had seized two container ships and fired on one.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] This was in response to the US seizing an Iranian ship three days earlier.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 22–23 April, three Iranian oil tankers were intercepted by the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Despite Iran's seizure of two cargo ships, Trump claimed total control over the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Guardian* described the situation as a "dual blockade", saying that while the US Navy could blockade Iranian ports, it had been unable to stop Iran's blockade and open the strait to allies.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel and Lebanon agreed a three-week extension of their ceasefire.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 24 April, Iran said it seized a ship suspected of collaborating with the Americans after the ship ignored warnings.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 April, Trump canceled US negotiators' trip to Pakistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 May, Trump said the US would help free up ships in the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 May, the UAE and Oman said they had intercepted Iranian missiles, and drones.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian state media said Iran's navy fired missiles and hit an American frigate.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM denied the missiles struck the ship.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US Forces destroyed six small Iranian boats after they allegedly attempted to interfere with the transit of two US flagged commercial ships and two destroyers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The UAE said an Iranian drone strike on an oil processing plant in Fujairah caused a fire, injuring Indian citizens.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 May, Trump announced a pause in the US military's "Project Freedom" to reopen the strait for "a short period", citing "great progress" toward an agreement with Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] *NBC News* reported that Trump's sudden announcement angered Saudi leaders who supported the diplomatic process in Pakistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Saudi Arabia responded by not allowing the US military to fly aircraft from Prince Sultan Air Base or fly through Saudi airspace, which forced the pause in operations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 May, the US said it had struck Iranian military sites in Bandar Abbas and Qeshm Island in response to a missile, drone, and boat attack on US destroyers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran accused the US of violating the truce by targeting an Iranian oil tanker and another vessel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] It said the US strikes hit civilian areas in Qeshm Island, and coastal areas in Bandar Khamir and Sirik.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it targeted American military vessels in response.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The UAE claimed that its air defense systems shot down Iranian ballistic missiles.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US said that it carried out strikes on two oil tankers allegedly attempting to reach Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian officials said that six people went missing and others were injured in US attacks, which hit "Iranian fishing and cargo vessels".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 May, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Israel constructed a military base in a desert region of Iraq to support its air campaign, and launched airstrikes against Iraqi soldiers who almost found the base, killing a soldier.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 May, Iraqi officials confirmed another base in Iraq was held by Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 10 May, UAE and Kuwait reported drone incursions that were neutralized, and a fire on a vessel off Qatar following a drone attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The next day, the US dispatched the submarine USS Alaska (SSBN-732) to Gibraltar to put pressure on Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] *The Wall Street Journal* reported that the UAE has been discreetly striking Iran, including a strike on an oil refinery on Lavan Island in April, and that the UAE was coordinating with Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US Ambassador to Israel Mike Huckabee announced that Israel had sent Iron Dome batteries, and personnel, to the UAE, to deter Iranian assaults.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 12 May, Kuwait accused Iran of attempting to infiltrate Bubiyan Island on 1 May with six troops of the IRGC.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 13 May, Reuters reported that Saudi Arabia had struck Iranian-backed Iraqi militias near the Iraq–Saudi Arabia border around the time of the 7 April US-Iran ceasefire.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Kuwait launched attacks on Iraqi militias from its territory.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Netanyahu's office said he covertly visited the UAE during the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 May, Trump said he postponed a "scheduled attack" on Iran for 19 May at the request of Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 24 May, a US official said that the US and Iran theoretically agreed for Tehran to reopen Hormuz and dispose of highly enriched uranium.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian media reported that Iran intercepted an Israeli Orbiter surveillance drone in its Hormozgan province.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said it was unaware of any such incident.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 May, the US struck targets in Iran, including boats and missile sites.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to Iranian sources, prior to the US attacks, the Iranians targeted a ship.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 26 May, Iran said it had downed a US MQ-9 drone and fired towards a fighter jet in its airspace.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] It claimed a US RQ-4 drone and F-35 fighter jet entered its airspace prior to retreating.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 27 May, the US conducted strikes in Iran targeting a military site which officials believed threatened American forces in the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 May, Kuwait downed a ballistic missile launched at its territory.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it had targeted the American base in Kuwait responsible for the previous day's attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Debris from the downed Fateh-110 missile fell on Ali Al Salem Air Base, injuring American soldiers and contractors, and destroying a US Reaper drone.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 June, US Central Command announced that a Hellfire missile launched from a American jet disabled a tanker heading for Kharg Island, after the vessel "ignored warnings" and did not comply with the US blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 June, Iran said it had targeted the US Fifth Fleet headquarters, and an ‌airbase and helicopters, with missiles and drones in response to an American attack on communication towers near Qeshm Island.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] It stated that its navy targeted a ship called *Panaya* using missiles in response to an American attack on an Iranian tanker.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US Central Command said Iranian missiles fired towards Kuwait fell short ‌or broke apart in flight, while ballistic missiles launched towards regional targets failed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said the US military shot down Iranian drones "targeting civilian ships" in regional waters and American forces in Kuwait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] One person was killed during attacks that hit Kuwait airport.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran denied responsibility, claiming the destruction was caused by a malfunction in a US-made Patriot air defence system.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 5 June, CNN reported that Israel had secretly deployed military personnel to Azerbaijan and was operating a facility in Somaliland.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it launched warning missiles and drones towards American warships in the Gulf of Oman.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US rejected the claim, saying doing so would be a violation of the truce.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 June, the US announced that it downed Iranian drones fired toward the strait and hit coastal surveillance radar sites in Sirik and Qeshm Island, as a response.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran announced that it had targeted US air bases in Kuwait and a US navy site in Bahrain with ballistic missiles, after the attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said that of the seven Iranian missiles launched, six were shot down and one failed to reach its target.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 June, the US announced that it downed Iranian drones posing a threat to the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Lebanese ⁠state media said an Israeli strike in the suburbs of Beirut killed two people.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The IDF said that it targeted Hezbollah infrastructure after the group fired towards Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said that American bases and Israeli assets in the Middle East are legitimate targets due to the American blockade and Israeli strikes on Beirut's suburbs, where Hezbollah members live.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran launched ballistic missiles towards Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran targeted Ramat David Airbase and Israel confirmed that the base was damaged.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel said that it will retaliate "forcefully" to the Iranian violation of the truce.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 8 June, the IDF announced that it struck military sites in Iran, with explosions reported in Tehran, Isfahan, and Tabriz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] This triggered an exchange between the two countries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Two Iranian soldiers were killed in an Israeli attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran afterwards said it had ceased military actions against Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel stopped strikes at Trump's request.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 June, *The New York Times* reported that American crew was rescued after a helicopter went down near the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said they were rescued by a US Navy drone boat for the first time.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said Iranians had shot down the helicopter and pledged to respond.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] A US official said a Shahed one-way attack drone downed the helicopter.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said it did not deliberately target the helicopter.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM later said that it launched "self-defense" strikes in retaliation.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] One attack damaged water reservoir tanks in Sirik; Iran stated that 20,000 people had lost access to drinking water.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 10 June, Iran said that it launched strikes aimed at the US Fifth Fleet, Ali Al Salem airbase and Muwaffaq Salti Air Base in retaliation to the US attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump promised to strike Iran "very hard", citing inadequate progress in negotiations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said US forces disabled an oil tanker in the Gulf of Oman which allegedly violated its blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Indian External Affairs Ministry condemned the attack in which three Indian crew were killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An Associated Press source said that the tanker received warnings prior to the American strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said that the US military secretly facilitated the passage of 100 million barrels of oil across the Strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US military launched strikes on Iranian targets on 10 June, firing 49 Tomahawk missiles.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] US attacks with precision munition allegedly targeted facilities for providing drinking water near Bemani.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Local authorities claimed 20,000 people were cut off from water supplies.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 11 June, Iran announced the closure of the Strait to oil tankers and commercial ships, threatening to fire upon any vessel attempting to pass and claimed to have struck two ships allegedly trying to transit the strait, claims denied by the US military.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran reported launching attacks on antennas and radar facilities of the Patriot system located at American military bases in Kuwait and Bahrain, as well as on a US command center in Jordan, in retaliation.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Downed Iranian drones landed in populated areas of Bahrain, causing damage to houses.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM executed a strike with Hellfire missiles on a ship in the Gulf of Oman, targeting its engine room while it was transporting Iranian oil.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The ship's crew, all Indian nationals, allegedly did not follow directions from American forces but were rescued.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump announced that the US would take control of Iran's oil and gas markets like it did in Venezuela, stating this would happen soon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] He threatened to strike Iran "VERY HARD TONIGHT" and seize Kharg Island and other oil infrastructure.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump claimed that the US could take over Iran with small troop deployment, although he did not intend to.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump expressed skepticism about Americans' willingness to support an invasion of Kharg Island.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Key gaps regarding the release of frozen Iranian assets, reopening of the Hormuz, and protocols for managing Iran's nuclear program during a 60-day ceasefire were narrowed in talks between Iranian officials and Qatari mediators, coordinated with the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 12 June Pakistan announced that Iran-US peace agreement text was "agreed".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 14 June, Iran said that the draft US deal included Tehran agreeing not to produce or acquire nuclear weapons, and the US agreeing to allow Tehran to dilute its highly enriched uranium stockpile in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump and Iran announced they had reached an agreement to end the war and reopen the Strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump said he had authorized the lifting of the US blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 15 June, US vice president JD Vance announced that the memorandum was digitally signed by both countries the previous day.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 June, Trump stated that if he does not like the agreement with Iran, the US will "go right back to dropping bombs".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump and Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian signed the memorandum of understanding to end the war, with Trump signing it during dinner with French president Emmanuel Macron at the Palace of Versailles after the G7 summit.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 June, Pakistan stated that the signing of the memorandum implies Tehran will reopen the Hormuz "instantly" and the American blockade will end "immediately." CENTCOM announced that it had removed the naval blockade.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 19 June, US president Donald Trump announced a renewed ceasefire between Israel and Hezbollah in the 2026 Lebanon war, facilitated by the US, Qatar, and Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Hezbollah announced an attack on Israeli forces trying to capture Ali al-Taher in Nabatieh.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Israel continued to strike southern Lebanon numerous times.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 20 June, Iran declared that it closed the Strait of Hormuz again due to Israeli strikes in Lebanon, describing them as a violation of its deal with the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] This claim was denied by the US military.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Shipping was stalled in the Hormuz following Iran's claimed closure of the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Some vessels approaching the strait deactivated their automatic identification systems to cross near the Omani shoreline and avoid Iranian military detection.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump stated that there will be no tolls for passing through the Hormuz during or after the 60-day interim ceasefire with Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 21 June, Trump issued a threat to invade Iran if they closed the Hormuz, following Iran's claim of its closure.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the US and Iran agreed to establish a "hotline" to coordinate traffic in the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 25 June, Iran declared a new Hormuz route laid out by Oman and the International Maritime Organization "unacceptable and dangerous", warning against ships transiting with no approval from it.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the British military announced that a cargo vessel was damaged by an unknown projectile in the Hormuz 7.5 nautical miles southeast of Omani port of Dahit while travelling via the UN-approved route.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US accused Iran of carrying out the attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The International Maritime Organization chose to halt its planned evacuation of ships stranded around the Hormuz following the attack, causing oil prices to surge by much to 4%.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 26 June, Iranian state media reported that at least three foreign oil tankers which tried to cross the Hormuz "without authorisation" from Iran had turned back after an Iranian warning.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iranian state media announced that the United States and Iran had established a communication line in the Hormuz to prevent military confrontations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, tracking platforms showed that despite Iranian warnings, several ships crossed the Hormuz via Oman.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On that day, Trump accused Iran of violating the truce with US by launching drone attacks on ships in the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The United States Central Command later announced that in retaliation to the alleged truce violations, the US hit Iranian missile and drone storage facilities, as well as coastal radar stations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran said that its retaliation to the attack will ⁠be "swift and decisive," prior to deleting the ⁠statement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 27 June, Iran said it targeted American sites in the Gulf region in response to the attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the United Kingdom Maritime Trade Operations said that an unidentified projectile struck a tanker in the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] UKTMO added that the vessel's bridge was damaged, but all crew members were reported safe, and no environmental damage had been detected at the time of the report.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, the Joint Maritime Information Center (JMIC), which is overseen by the US Navy, announced that a route through the Hormuz near Oman has been widened to allow for more naval traffic in both directions, implying that the US is challenging Iran's control over the waterway.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump accused Iran of repeatedly violating the ceasefire memorandum, expressing doubt about their ability to learn from past mistakes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] He warned of a potential point where the US will be forced to militarily "complete the job", stating that if this occurs, the Iranian regime could cease to exist.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 June, Iran said it fired ballistic missiles and drones towards the US-operated Ali Al Salem Air Base in Kuwait and the US Fifth Fleet headquarters in Bahrain in retaliation to American attacks against five Iranian coastal sites.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iranian state television stated that passing through the Hormuz still required coordination with Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Iran stated that the Hormuz would stay under Iranian control for 30 days and the Islamabad Memorandum grants Tehran control over the waterway.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On that day, a member of the Office of Preservation and Publication of Iran's Supreme Leader's Works told state TV that Iran cancelled participation in technical talks due to recent attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US and Iran later reportedly agreed to stop exchange of attacks between them and meet that week.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 29 June, Iran denied that technical meetings with Americans are expected for that week, referring to the Iranian week concluding on Friday.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Trump said that a US-Iran meeting would take place the next day in Doha, claiming that Iran requested the meeting.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Iran reiterated that no negotiations between Iran and Americans are scheduled in the coming days.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran later stated that it opposes vessels crossing outside of Tehran's designated Hormuz channels and will try to prevent them.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 30 June, Qatar confirmed that US envoy Steve Witkoff and Trump's son-in-law ‌Jared Kushner will be in Doha to meet Qatari mediators to discuss negotiations with Iran, but there will not be a high-level meeting between Americans and Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran announced that it was unable to export any oil during the US blockade of its ports.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, *The Wall Street Journal* reported, citing official US sources that Trump has discussed with Defence Secretary Pete Hegseth and Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Gen.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Dan Caine the prospect of more strikes against the Iranian regime.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to the sources, the discussions focused on whether the US should abandon negotiations and conduct an all-out war against the regime, a move some described as "finishing the job." According to reports, Trump has decided to stay on the diplomatic course for the time being.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Trump also stated that his deadline for a nuclear deal with Tehran is 18 August, and that he is comfortable if negotiations with Tehran extend past that date.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 July, Iranian state television broadcast on-screen alerts about what it falsely claimed as a foreign ship that got struck while rejecting the IRGC navy's orders.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The false claim looked to be intended to bolster Tehran's claim of sovereignty over the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Marine tracking data revealed that the ship is linked to the Iranian regime.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 July, Iran stated that IAEA inspectors will not be permitted entry under any circumstances to the Fordow, Natanz, and Isfahan nuclear sites, which were bombed and damaged by the US, citing a law passed by the Iranian parliament and the Supreme National Security Council.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, Iran cautioned oil tankers to take permitted routes through the Hormuz or risk a "forceful response".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 July, Trump mentioned the war in a speech commemorating the US' 250th anniversary, claiming Americans granted the Iranian regime a week off for a funeral.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the same day, the UK and France stated that Oman had committed to work with both countries to ensure safe navigation through its territorial waters in the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran warned the UK and France against providing military support to defend shipping in the Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The same day, Trump stated that the US could have killed regime officials attending former Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei's funeral, but doing so would have left no one to negotiate with.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US and Israel eliminated many Iranian commanders and leaders on the war's first day by causing Iran to believe that strikes were not imminent.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Thus, groups of senior Iranian officials continued gathering in person.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] These gatherings were targeted in initial strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] One part of the deception was information about a US F-22 deployment leaked to hide that preparations were more advanced at other bases.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Calls between Trump and Netanyahu before the war were not publicised to diminish the possibility of an Iranian first strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] IDF spokesperson Brigadier General Effie Defrin stated that months of joint US and Israeli "strategic and operational deception" of satellite imagery led up to the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] This encompassed planes and other facilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The night of the initial strike he and IDF Chief of Staff Lieutenant General Eyal Zamir took their official cars home from IDF Headquarters.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] They came back without them so that satellite imagery would show that their base did not appear full nor warplanes appear armed and ready.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Three separate gatherings of Iranian officials were hit within half a minute of each other in the opening strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 February 2026, Ali Khamenei, the supreme leader of Iran, was assassinated in an Israeli air attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, Iranian state media announced Khamenei's death.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The IRGC-controlled Fars News Agency announced that Khamenei's daughter, son-in-law, grandchild, and daughter-in-law Zahra Haddad-Adel had also been killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian government declared 40 days of mourning.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The initial dead included Iranian defense minister Aziz Nasirzadeh, and four top Ministry of Intelligence officials.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 13 March, IDF estimated that between 3,000 and 4,000 Iranian soldiers and commanders had been killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 March, Israel assassinated Ali Larijani, secretary of Iran's Supreme National Security Council.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] IRGC commander Mohammad Pakpour and Defence Council secretary Ali Shamkhani were reported dead in late March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 18 March, the Hengaw Organization for Human Rights estimated that 5,300+ members of the Iranian military had been killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 31 March, Iran International reported that at least 4,700 security forces had been killed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 6 April, the head of IRGC intelligence, Major General Majid Khademi, was assassinated in a joint US-Israeli airstrike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 7 April, Human Rights Activists in Iran (HRANA), a US-based non-governmental organization, reported 3,636 documented war deaths, including 1,701 civilians, 1,221 military personnel, and 714 unclassified.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to HRANA, "[i]t is believed that military casualties are significantly higher than the figures reported in [its] reports" as confirmations depend largely on government data.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Its count largely reflects reports of military personnel present in urban areas.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On the first day of the war, the Shajareh Tayyebeh girl's elementary school in Minab was hit by an American attack, according to Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The school was located near the Sayyid al-Shuhada military complex, of which it had once been a part.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] While the number killed was not independently confirmed, Iranian state media reported that more than 175 people, mostly children, were killed while 95 were wounded.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Video showed a Tomahawk missile hitting a building adjacent to the school; preliminary findings from an American military investigation indicated that the strike resulted from outdated targeting data.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] At least 20 civilians, mostly families who gathered after breaking their fast at Ramadan, were killed in Tehran's Niloofar Square on 1 or 2 March, according to Iranian-state media.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, the Iranian Red Crescent Society said that over 600 civilians had been killed while HRANA reported 1,097 civilian deaths.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 7 March, the Red Crescent reported that over 6,668 civilian "units" had been targeted by US-Israeli strikes, including 5,535 residential units, 1,041 commercial units, 14 medical centers, 65 schools, and 13 centers affiliated with the Red Crescent.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Middle East Eye, an anti-Israel news outlet, reported that the US used double tap airstrikes, although the US denies this.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 23 March, HRANA estimated that at least 15% of the casualties were under age 18.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An Israeli airstrike on 9 March in Resalat neighbourhood of Tehran destroyed a Basij-affiliated building as well as three residential buildings, killing 40 to 50.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to a BBC analysis, Israel used Mark 82 bombs in the attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] As of 27 March, Iran has reported damage to at least 120 historical sites.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The deadly attack on residential buildings and a sports hall in the town of Lamerd killed 21 including 4 children and injured 100.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The initial attack targeted Leadership House.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 2 March, video footage released by Iran International showed the destroyed IRGC Malek-Ashtar building in Tehran following a joint US-Israel missile strike.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, the complex of Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting (IRIB), the state broadcaster's headquarters, was hit in an Israeli air operation.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian state-linked media indicated that Iran's parliament building was targeted.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 3 March, Israeli forces bombed the Assembly of Experts office building in Qom.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] By 5 March, the World Health Organization had identified 13 Iranian health sites hit, as well as one in Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian Foreign Minister said that the US had struck a desalination plant on Qeshm Island, disrupting water supply to 30 villages, but both the US and Israel denied an attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Russian consulate in Isfahan was damaged.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] After US strikes on 9 June, Iran said that damage to water storage units in Hormozgan province had left 20,000 people without water.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Analysis of satellite images by *the Washington Post* revealed damages to at least 228 structures or pieces of equipment at US bases across the Persian Gulf, far more than the Trump administration has admitted to.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, six US soldiers were killed amid more than 30 injured in an Iranian drone attack near Camp Arifjan in Port Shuaiba, Kuwait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Those killed were soldiers of the United States Army Reserve assigned to the 103rd Expeditionary Sustainment Command, headquartered in Des Moines, Iowa.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 March, US Marine Corps Lance Corporal Kevin Melendez died in Saudi Arabia in a non-hostile incident.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 8 March, CENTCOM reported that a National Guard soldier died during a medical emergency.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Pennington, a soldier of the 1st Space Brigade wounded in an attack against Prince Sultan Air Base in Saudi Arabia on 1 March, died from his injuries on 9 March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Six American airmen were killed on 12 March when their KC-135 aerial refueling aircraft crashed in western Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] CENTCOM said that the crash was not the result of hostile action, but had resulted during an incident involving another US aircraft.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] By 13 March, the US military publicly announced that about 140 American servicemen had been injured.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] A 27 March attack on Prince Sultan Air Base damaged "multiple" refueling aircraft and destroyed a Boeing E-3 Sentry, as well as wounding at least 15 US soldiers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Ford*, the largest aircraft carrier in theatre, was damaged by a fire that broke out 12 March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The US Navy said the fire had injured multiple sailors, started in a laundry area and was not combat-related.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The carrier had been dealing with other mechanical issues, including a malfunctioning sewage treatment system, since before it arrived in the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to multiple reports on 17–18 March, *Gerald R.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Ford* paused launching airstrikes and sailed toward the Crete Naval Base for repairs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Many US military bases near Iran were rendered "all but uninhabitable" due to Iranian strikes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Within the war's first two weeks, Iran's attacks caused $800 million in damage to bases.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Affected bases include Al-Sader and Al-Ruwais in the UAE, the naval base in Bahrain, Ali Al-Salem in Kuwait, Al-Udeid in Qatar, and Prince Sultan in Saudi Arabia.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to unnamed officials, the damage degraded the US's military ability in the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Many US servicemembers relocated to "hotels and office spaces", which raised concerns of the US using civilians as human shields.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] An attack on a hotel in Bahrain injured two Pentagon employees.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Based on numbers given by members of the United States Congress, by May 2026 the United States military had lost 39 aircraft in "Operation Epic Fury".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Magen David Adom reported that Iran's initial attacks had left 89 injured, with three directly wounded and the rest indirectly, most of them civilians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 28 February, a direct hit in Tel Aviv killed a woman and injured 22 others, one seriously.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 March, a strike hit a synagogue and residential buildings in Beit Shemesh, killing nine civilians in a shelter and injuring 49 others.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 9 March, two workers were killed in Yehud, outside of Tel Aviv, after they were struck by submunitions from an Iranian missile equipped with a cluster bomb warhead.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 17 March, a cluster munition from an Iranian warhead hit an apartment building in Ramat Gan and killed two residents.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] A statement from the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps called the missile barrage "revenge for the blood of martyr Dr.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Ali Larijani and his companions", who had been killed the day before in a targeted attack.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] According to CNN, the use of cluster munitions violates international law.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Jenzen-Jones of Armament Research Services stated that this type of warhead is being used "primarily to sow terror amongst a civilian population".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 4 April, an Iranian missile strike hit in the vicinity of the IDF's Kirya headquarters in Tel Aviv.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Since 2 March 2026, there has been an ongoing war in Lebanon between Israel and the Lebanese Shia militant group Hezbollah, with Israel invading parts of Lebanon.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] It is a resumption of major fighting in the Hezbollah–Israel conflict that began in late 2023, and is part of the wider conflict in the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In Iraq, two members of the Iran-backed Popular Mobilization Forces (PMF) were killed and three injured in a US-Israeli attack on 28 February.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] On 1 and 2 March, the United States and Israel conducted several attacks on Iranian-backed Iraqi militias to degrade their military capabilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] In addition to Israel, Iran launched strikes against multiple US-allied Arab countries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iranian strikes against Bahrain killed three.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against Kuwait killed four soldiers and four civilians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against Saudi Arabia killed two.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Strikes against the United Arab Emirates killed two soldiers and six civilians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] Iran also struck Qatar, Azerbaijan, and the Akrotiri and Dhekelia British Overseas Territory on Cyprus.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p03] The Iranian attacks affected military infrastructure from NATO countries in the region, "including an Italian installation in Iraq and Kuwait, and a French naval facility in the United Arab Emirates".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The death of Ali Khamenei triggered an election for a new supreme leader.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Under the terms of Iran's constitution, the Interim Leadership Council was established on 1 March to exercise the functions of Iran's head of state until a new supreme leader is elected.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Mojtaba Khamenei was elected on 8 March 2026 to replace his father as supreme leader, and the IRGC, as well as Iran's top leaders, including Mohammad Bagher Ghalibaf, Ali Larijani, and Masoud Pezeshkian, pledged their allegiance to him.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In late March, the NYT described Iran's leadership as paralyzed with severely disrupted decision-making process.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] It also reported that the damage to communications infrastructure caused paranoia and internal power struggles.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As of 21 May, Khamenei remains in hiding and the de facto ruler is uncertain.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The IRGC is currently under command of the hardliner general Ahmad Vahidi, who is cited as the formulator of Iran's military and negotiation stance.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to UN Human Rights Chief Volker Türk, the "reckless" war is disproportionately impacting civilians in the Middle East and beyond.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] 138,000 civilian sites in Iran were damaged during the conflict, with estimated time of reconstruction being 2 to 5 years.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As the US and Israel executed joint strikes targeting Iranian military and institutional targets, Iran's capital reportedly became a ghost town, as civilians feared going outside or to their daily jobs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Reports have emerged that prisoners in Evin Prison have been receiving limited bread and water since the onset of the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] After the strikes, schools were ordered closed while banks and government offices remained in operation at reduced capacity.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Local media reported that subway and bus services would remain operational.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Amid the renewed "near total" internet blackout in Iran, NetBlocks reported that internet connectivity in Iran dropped to 4% of ordinary levels.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] While the internet blackout has exceeded 240 hours, making it the second longest ever, the government started handing out "white sim cards", which bypass filters, to government supporters, in order to allow them to promote its messaging.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As news of Khamenei's death broke, security forces were deployed to prevent an uprising, with footage showing them opening fire on celebrants in the streets and shooting at people chanting behind the windows of their homes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] During the first two weeks of March 2026, over 70,000 Afghan refugees returned to Afghanistan, frequently under forced circumstances, exacerbating the country's severe humanitarian crisis.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Arafat Jamal, the UNHCR Representative in Afghanistan, noted that they faced limited options amid the military confrontations between Afghanistan and Pakistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to *The Guardian*, the war has overshadowed the executions of political prisoners in Iran, including those involved in the mass protests of January 2026, allowing Iran to continue carrying out death sentences and other severe punishments with little international scrutiny.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to several Iran-focused human rights groups, the rate of sentencing and executions by hanging has surged over the past two months amid the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The groups state that in most of these cases, the executed prisoners did not receive due process.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 26 March, it was reported that children as young as 12 years of age may join Iran's war support, leading to concerns of the use of child soldiers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Days later, rights groups stated an 11-year-old was killed while on duty at a Tehran checkpoint.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 29 March, footage showed Iraq's Popular Mobilization Forces deployed in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, Trump had been open to supporting armed militias, particularly Kurds in Iran that have been in armed conflict with Tehran for decades and have historically been a regional ally of the United States.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] However, Trump later said he had ruled out sending the Kurds to Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Multiple historic and cultural sites, including UNESCO World Heritage Sites, were damaged during the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The most affected was Chehel Sotoun and its rich *ayeneh-kari*.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 2 March, a strike on Arg Square damaged nearby Golestan Palace, prompting UNESCO to issue a statement of concern.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 5 March, the Azadi Sport Complex was bombed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] An 8 March strike on Falak-ol-Aflak, which was marked with a blue shield emblem, damaged several sections of the site.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Strikes on Isfahan on 9 March damaged Naqsh-e Jahan Square, Chehel Sotoun, Ali Qapu, the Shah Mosque, Jameh Mosque, and Teymouri Hall.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 11 March, UNESCO urged protection for Iran's heritage sites and World Heritage Sites that have been damaged or are under high risk due to the war, alongside other historic sites in Israel, Lebanon, and the rest of West Asia.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 March, blast waves and sharpnel damaged multiple palaces at Sa'dabad Complex in northern Tehran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Russia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs reported that strikes in Tehran on 1 April damaged the St.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Nicholas Orthodox Church and it's auxiliary buildings.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 7 April, the Rafi'-Nia synagogue was fully destroyed by the Israeli Air Force.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israel declared a nationwide state of emergency, saying that the strikes on Iran were the largest that it had ever launched.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli schools and workspaces were closed and public gatherings were canceled.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In the 40 days from the start of the war through the 8 April ceasefire, there were a total of 650 missile attacks from Iran to Israel, the majority of which carried cluster munitions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] About 16 of the missiles that made it past Israeli missile defenses carried conventional warheads, while 50 had cluster munitions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The attacks killed a total of 24 people, all of them civilians, and resulted in more than 7,000 injuries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Of the 24 civilians killed, 14 were struck by warheads with conventional explosive warheads and 10 were victims of cluster submunitions; two of the deaths were inside a sheltered space, with the other fatalities being people in unprotected areas.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Israeli Coordinator of Government Activities in the Territories closed multiple aid crossings in the Gaza Strip, specifically interrupting free circulation on the Egypt–Gaza border.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli forces suspended United Nations humanitarian movements and postponed planned rotations of international humanitarian staff, including medical evacuations and the return of people into Gaza, which the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs condemned.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli settler violence against Palestinians in occupied West Bank has increased; settlers have taken advantage of curbs on movement imposed during the renewed Israeli state of emergency.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The renewed blocking of West Bank roads in the context of the 2026 Lebanon war has delayed medics from assisting injured Palestinians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The EU stated on 10 March that the Israeli actions were unacceptable and urged the Israeli authorities to make immediate efforts to prevent the violence against Palestinian civilians under international law, warning that "impunity for such acts risks provoking further violence".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Lebanon states more than one million people, 1/6th of the population, were displaced.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Arab states of the Persian Gulf started a campaign of prosecution against civilians and foreign citizens that shared or reposted rumours from unverified sources about the Iranian attacks, with the stated main goal to curb misinformation that could harm public order.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump said "Even if we knew Gulf countries would be hit, big deal we did what we have to do".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Saudi Arabia invoked its Strategic Mutual Defence Agreement with Pakistan.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Pakistan deployed some 8,000 troops, a squadron of 16 aircraft, and two squadrons of drones.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] There was a pledge to send more if required.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 28 May, the US president Donald Trump threatened to 'blow up' Oman if it fails to "behave" in a casual aside during a cabinet meeting after reports of talks between Iran and Oman about jointly charging a toll for ships passing through the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Airstrikes on industrial and fuel hubs have released a chronic toxic cocktail of benzene, heavy metals, and persistent 'forever chemicals' (PFAS), triggering 'black rain' in major cities and causing long-term health degradation for civilians.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The war had global economic consequences: oil and gas prices surged, aviation and tourism were disrupted, and financial markets shuddered.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] International Energy Agency (IEA) head Fatih Birol described the situation as the "greatest global energy security challenge in history".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Oil and natural gas prices rose in direct response to Iranian threats to attack tankers and other ships and to Iranian strikes on oil facilities in Gulf producing countries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] 20% of global oil and gas production normally transit the Strait of Hormuz.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As the war continued, oil and gas prices ebbed and flowed as markets attempted to assess the likelihood of an end to the conflict.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Prices ranged from below $70 before the war to as high as $139 on 7 March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Following the start of the war, multiple oil producers such as Shell, TotalEnergies, Britain's BP and others announced increased profits in their first quarter.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Toward the end of March significant shortages of domestic petroleum products emerged in southeast Asia as reserves ran out.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Stock markets initially fell, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average falling over 400 points (one percent) on 2 March alone, although by mid-April had recovered and reached record highs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The UN World Food Programme and various economic analysts warned that the war is driving significant, long-term increases in global food prices.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran, which had access to the strait, had an increase in revenues.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Disruption in the supply of essential fertilizers due to the closure of the Strait threatened food production in many countries.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Fertilizer Institute stated that nearly 50% of global urea and sulfur exports annually transited through the Strait of Hormuz, made worse by the natural gas shortage, which is a key feedstock for nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran's airspace emptied of civilian aircraft during the conflict, as Bahrain, Iraq, Israel, Kuwait, Qatar, Syria and the UAE closed their respective airspaces.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Some carriers suspended service to the Middle East.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The disruption in global oil supply, caused by the closure of the Strait of Hormuz during the conflict, led to higher jet fuel prices, which increased operating costs for airlines and pushed up airfares on both domestic and international routes.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Airlines responded by raising ticket prices and adjusting some flight schedules to cope with higher fuel costs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] This impact was also visible in Europe, where continued disruptions in energy supply routes contributed to higher fuel prices and additional pressure on airlines.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As a result, some carriers reduced capacity or cut flights, while others passed increased costs directly on to passengers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Spirit Airlines, an American low-cost airline, ceased operations on 2 May 2026, after increased fuel costs from the war exacerbated its existing financial difficulties.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Shipping traffic through the Strait of Hormuz, a major maritime choke point for world energy trade, has been largely blocked by Iran since 28 February 2026, when the United States and Israel launched an air war against Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In retaliation, the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) issued warnings forbidding passage through the strait, boarded and attacked merchant ships, and laid sea mines in the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] From 13 April to 29 May 2026, the US simultaneously blockaded Iranian ports.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Until the war's start, about 25% of the world's seaborne oil trade and 20% of the world's liquefied natural gas (LNG) passed through the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Soon after the start of the conflict, tanker traffic dropped to almost nothing.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 27 March, the IRGC announced that the strait was closed to any vessel going "to and from" the ports of the US, Israel, and their allies.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The International Maritime Organization reported on 21 April that about 20,000 mariners and 2,000 ships were stranded in the Persian Gulf due to the closure.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Amid fears of prolonged supply shortages, oil prices rose faster than during any other conflict in recent history; Brent crude oil prices surpassed US$100 per barrel on 8 March for the first time in four years, rising to US$126 per barrel at their peak.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The largest-ever monthly increase in oil prices occurred in March 2026.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The closure of the strait became the largest disruption to world energy supply since the 1970s energy crisis as well as the largest in the history of the world oil market.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Other commodity markets to suffer supply disruption and price increases due to the crisis include aluminum, fertilizer, and helium.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In late March and early April, US president Donald Trump repeatedly threatened to destroy Iran's infrastructure if it did not reopen the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 8 April a temporary ceasefire between Iran and the US was agreed and was to involve the reopening of the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] However, following the failure of the Islamabad Talks, the US Navy itself began to blockade Iranian ports from 13 April.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The situation was described by *The Guardian* as a "dual blockade", with the US Navy blockading Iran and Iran blockading the Gulf.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 April, Iran announced that due to an Israel–Lebanon ceasefire agreement, it would allow commercial shipping, but the US continued its blockade of Iran, and Iran reimposed restrictions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 4 May, Trump launched Operation Project Freedom, a US Navy mission to escort merchant ships out of the Gulf.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Iranian military warned that this would be a ceasefire violation, and on 6 May, Trump paused Project Freedom because of "great progress" toward a possible agreement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 17 June, Trump and Iranian president Masoud Pezeshkian signed a memorandum of understanding to end the war and the blockades of the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 19 June, Trump announced a renewed ceasefire between Israel and Hezbollah, facilitated by the US, Qatar, and Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] However, Israel continued strikes in southern Lebanon, and the following day, Iran said that it closed the strait again, citing the Israeli actions as a violation of the agreement, a claim denied by the US military.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 27 June, the Joint Maritime Information Center (JMIC) overseen by the US Navy announced a widened route through the Strait of Hormuz near Oman, allowing increased naval traffic in both directions and indicating a challenge to Iran's control over the waterway.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Houthi-controlled Yemen threatened shipping in the Gulf of Aden and Red Sea.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Its threats had been suspended since 10 October 2025.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] March threats by Houthi leader Abdul-Malik al-Houthi had not stopped Red Sea traffic as of mid-April, although traffic remained under historic levels after crashing in 2024 as a result of Houthi attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 15 March, the *Associated Press* reported that the weapons stockpile of the Houthis was running low from repeated attacks on Israel, while Iran had not been able to resupply them, because of the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Fundamental web infrastructure including S3 storage, EC2 compute and DynamoDB databases suffered complete outages in early March.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran shut down Internet access for its people throughout the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Users who took the potentially fatal risk of smuggling Starlink terminals into the country retained some access.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to a new report by the Center for International Policy, the US spent nearly $72 billion on the war ($1.2 billion per day on average).
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The figure is nearly three times the amount of the Pentagon's official estimate.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] US military costs were estimated at $25–35 billion as of early April.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli costs were estimated at $11 billion.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Costs to the Iranian economy were estimated at $40–50 billion, around 10% of GDP.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The monetary costs of Iranian attacks were much lower than the costs of neutralizing them: PATRIOT and THAAD interceptors are $4 million and $12 million, respectively, as opposed to $50,000 for a Shahed drone.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The war has also increased indirect military costs due to the rapid depletion of US munitions stockpiles.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to reports, the United States has used large quantities of high-cost interceptors such as Patriot and THAAD missiles, further increasing replacement expenses and strain on defense budgets.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The depletion of stockpiles has also affected US arms transfers and procurement decisions, including reports that Washington is reconsidering or delaying the transfer of Tomahawk cruise missiles to Germany and reviewing Germany's request for Typhon launchers due to limited availability.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Reports also indicate delays in missile deliveries to Japan and new procurement efforts, including an $842 million agreement for JASSM-ER cruise missiles from Denmark.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] US officials have raised concerns that existing stockpiles may be insufficient for sustained operations in multiple theaters, including in the event of a future conflict in Asia.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Pentagon has also expanded efforts to increase production capacity through programs aimed at scaling lower-cost "affordable mass" munitions and involving non-traditional defense contractors.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The US defence industry saw record stock surges during the war.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Before hostilities erupted, media attention on US-Iran tensions increased in early 2026, following failed nuclear talks and domestic unrest in Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iranian state media, such as the IRNA, portrayed these developments as provocations.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iranian state-controlled outlets have been described as employing propaganda techniques, including the use of AI-generated videos (such as those produced by Explosive Media) and inflated casualty figures.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump has accused Iran of using artificial intelligence as a "disinformation weapon." Iranian media broadcast manipulated images of alleged victories, prompting fact-checking from organizations like NewsGuard.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The video declares itself in remembrance of the Minab school attack and showcases Iran attacking various of its neighbours and American-Israeli outposts.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Before hostilities erupted, media attention on US-Iran tensions increased in early 2026, following failed nuclear talks and reports of Iranian domestic unrest.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Outlets such as CNN and *The New York Times* detailed US military buildups in the region, speculating about possible attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Israeli broadcasters focused on the threats posed by Iranian proxies such as Hezbollah.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In May 2026, *Israel Hayom* reported that Mossad had established a dedicated influence operations branch in 2021 under director David Barnea.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] According to the report, the unit conducted psychological and media campaigns targeting Iran through social media networks, online influencers, artificial intelligence–generated content, and the dissemination of information intended to undermine confidence in the Iranian government.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] A former senior Mossad official identified only as "O." stated that encouraging political change in Iran had become one of the agency's central objectives.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The report further alleged that the branch had participated in efforts to publicize compromising information about Iranian officials, influence public opinion during periods of unrest, and support broader Israeli strategies aimed at weakening the Islamic Republic's political stability.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Rumors that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had been killed in Iranian attacks were circulating widely on social media and were amplified by Iranian state-controlled outlets.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Netanyahu responded by posting several videos, including one filmed in a Jerusalem cafe in which he sarcastically declared that he was "dying for coffee" while holding up a cappuccino and holding up his hands to show that he had five fingers.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The cafe video itself quickly became the subject of fresh rumors, with some social media users and commentators claiming that it too was AI-generated or a deepfake.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The cafe later released images as evidence that Netanyahu had visited.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Since the signing of the Islamabad Memorandum, the Israeli reactions to Trump and the declared end of hostilities towards Iran had been largely negative, with many expressing feelings of outrage and betrayal.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] For instance, *Israel Hayom* wrote in its headline "You could have been the greatest president of all, but you failed" and accused Trump of signing a surrender agreement and having humiliated his own country.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] As the airstrikes began, initial reporting relied heavily on satellite imagery and official briefings.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The Pentagon's announcements of the destruction of Iranian assets were widely echoed, but independent verification proved difficult due to Tehran's communications restrictions.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *Slate* criticized American news coverage of the war, arguing that headlines too often treat statements from the Trump administration as objective and fail to also cover points of contradiction by Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The White House faced backlash over a video that mixed real war footage with video game clips.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Critics said such efforts distorted public understanding.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] PBS argued The Trump administration's use of video game footage, cartoon and blockbuster movie scenes for Iran messaging "risks reducing a real war to spectacle".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump has repeatedly shared provocative images regarding the Iran war such as a map of the US flag over Iran with words reading "United States of the Middle East?" and an AI-generated image of Iranian ships being bombed.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The White House circulates videos fusing real airstrike footages with visuals from video games and action movies, "transforming acts of destruction into a spectacle of national triumph", keeping the audience detached from the human suffering it produces.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Artists and entertainment companies often object to their works use in such clips.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Kesha's song "Blow" was used alongside footage of an airstrike and the caption "Lethality", which prompted the singer to post on X, "Stop using my music, perverts @WhiteHouse".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Blase Cupich, an American Catholic Cardinal who is close with Pope Leo XIV, referred to a video released by the White House of attacks on Iran mixed with Hollywood film clips as "horrifying" and "sickening".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 14 March 2026, Federal Communications Commission chairman Brendan Carr, a Trump appointee, warned broadcasters that those who "perpetrate fake news and distort the news" must "take the right course" or risk losing their licenses at renewal.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Carr said broadcasters "must act in the public interest, and if they don't, they will lose their licenses," citing the public's low trust in legacy media and past election coverage problems.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump expressed that he was "enthusiastic" about Carr's stance.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In response to opposition of the war from Pope Leo XIV, Trump falsely claimed that the pope supported Iran having nuclear weapons and shared provocative memes on social media.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth also criticized the coverage during a news conference, taking issue with CNN's reporting and suggesting emphasizing Iranian frustration rather than adding to the headlines.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Democratic lawmakers condemned the FCC's remarks as unconstitutional censorship, with many calling it "oppressive" and a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 3 June 2026, the US House passed an act with a vote of 215-208 requiring the United States' war efforts to cease or gain approval from Congress to continue fighting.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On 23 June 2026, the US Senate enacted an act by a vote of 50-48 mandating the United States to either end its war operations or seek congressional consent to continue fighting.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] News media and traders have repeatedly applied the pejorative abbreviation "Trump Always Chickens Out" (TACO), previously used first for the Liberation Day tariffs, for Trump's repeated refusals to enforce his "red line" threats against Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Another pejorative abbreviation called "Not A Chance Hormuz Opens" (NACHO) was devised in reference to Trump's inability to quickly reopen the strait.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *CNN* observed that over the course of the war, Trump's repeated talking points, such as his claim that Iran's military had been destroyed and another that Iranian leadership supposedly really wants to make a deal with Trump regarding the war, had been stated baselessly for months.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *The Atlantic* argued that it was Trump who was visibly desperate for a deal and that Iran is able to exploit his needs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *Al-Monitor* reported that Netanyahu and his inner political circle view Trump's insistence on a deal as disastrous and blame him for failing to achieve regime change and victory against Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *The Sunday Guardian* wrote that despite the US having a military advantage, Trump was unwilling to commit to defeating the Islamic Republic and made the US appear as if it was losing to Iran, referring to him as "coward-in-chief".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] New reports have determined suspicious insider trading patterns within the stock and oil markets in correlation with "positive" news of the war from Trump over several months.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Wall Street analysts and Iranian state media had accused journalist Barak Ravid of *Axios* of repeating false information from anonymous sources regarding ongoing negotiations to allow for market manipulation of oil prices.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *The Wall Street Journal* argued that Trump directly intervened in the oil market by "jawboning" it, posting "positive" news of supposed negotiations to kill momentum of oil price increases by traders in quick responses to "negative" news.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] *CNN* observed that Trump incorrectly claimed that the US was close to an agreement with Iran to end the war more than 35 times from late March to early June, many of which involved Trump portraying Iran as supposedly "desperate".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Analysts accused Western media of failing to challenge the official narrative, with Mondoweiss highlighting the flattering language that downplayed civilian casualties.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Al Jazeera English noted the overrepresentation of voices from the pro-war Iranian diaspora.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Pre-war coverage was also marred by inadequate public warnings.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] On April 12, 2025, Iran and the United States began a series of negotiations aimed at reaching a nuclear peace agreement, following a letter from US president Donald Trump to Iranian supreme leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump set a 60-day deadline for Iran to reach an agreement.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] After the deadline passed without an agreement, Israel launched numerous strikes against Iran, igniting a war between the two countries in June.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The first round of high-level meetings was held in Oman on April 12, 2025, led by US special envoy Steve Witkoff and Iranian foreign minister Abbas Araghchi.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] At the time, both the White House and the Iranian Foreign Ministry said that the discussions held were constructive.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] A second round of Omani-mediated talks took place in Rome on April 19, 2025, again with indirect discussions between Witkoff and Araghchi.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] This was followed by a third round in Muscat around a week later, and an expert-level meeting to develop a framework for a possible nuclear agreement was led by Michael Anton for the US and by Majid Takht-Ravanchi for Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] After concluding that continued hostilities would risk economic calamity, Donald Trump signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU) on behalf of the United States during a ceremony at the Palace of Versailles on 17 June 2026.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The signing followed an earlier, digital signing of the MOU by the foreign ministers of the two principal belligerents.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In the MOU, the United States and Iran agreed to suspend hostilities for 60 days and to establish a framework for a permanent peace under which the US would make major financial and political concessions to the Islamic Republic of Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Trump characterized the MOU as representing the "unconditional surrender" of Iran.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Iran declared the document as an enduring "record of US failure".
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The *Foreign Policy*, and *The Atlantic* described the outcome of the war as a "defeat" for the United States and Israel.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Moving forward, Iranian chief negotiator Mohammad Bagher Ghalibaf stated Iran would unilaterally begin imposing permanent tolls on ships passing the Strait of Hormuz 60 days following the withdrawal of the US Navy.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The war helped entrench the power of the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps within Iranian politics and society, and, according to Robert Pape, began the process of transforming Iran into a major power.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] US vice-president Vance announced on 22 June 2026 that in negotiations in Switzerland, Iran would again accede to the inspection of their nuclear facilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The content of the vice-president's statement were not confirmed by Iranian sources subsequently in a publication of June 23.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The 2026 Iran war has been analysed in terms of its possible military and political consequences for the Islamic Republic of Iran, and from international legal and geopolitical standpoints.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] A number of analysts have argued that, despite massive military and economic damage to Iran and the killing of large portions of the country's leadership, on a strategic level the war has been a success for Iran and a failure for the United States.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In turn, Iran demonstrated that it could threaten US bases, undermining a widespread image of American military invulnerability.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Many experts argue that the war is illegal under US law because launching a war requires congressional authorization.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] They are also considered to be in violation of the UN Charter's prohibition on the use of force, because the attacks fail to meet the criteria for self-defense and lack authorization from the United Nations Security Council.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In response, the Trump administration claimed that previous presidents have also launched unauthorized military actions, and dismissed international law.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] In international criminal law, experts have identified the attacks as a crime of aggression, specifically as a war of aggression.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] The US attack also violates the Algiers Accords (1981) in which the US agreed not to intervene politically or militarily in Iran's internal affairs.
[src:bomb-disposal/2026-iran-war-p04] Numerous critics and analysts identified the US-Israeli attack with a more open embrace of expansionism and imperialism by the Trump administration, and a departure from the norms of the liberal international order.
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] The unit was previously titled 321 EOD Unit, then 321 EOD Company Royal Army Ordnance Corps (RAOC).
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] It was re-badged as a unit of the Royal Logistic Corps in April 1993, now part of 11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Regiment RLC.
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] With its headquarters at Alexander Barracks, Aldergrove near Antrim, the unit covers the entire province of Northern Ireland.
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] The unit is honoured at the Palace Barracks memorial garden.
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] It remains the most decorated unit in the British Army.
[src:bomb-disposal/321-eod] 321 is a well equipped unit and has been at the forefront of developing new equipment.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The **82nd Academy Awards** ceremony, presented by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), honored the best films of 2009 and took place on March 7, 2010, at the Kodak Theatre in Hollywood, Los Angeles, beginning at 5:30 p.m.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The ceremony was scheduled after its usual late-February date to avoid conflicting with the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] During the ceremony, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences presented Academy Awards (commonly referred to as Oscars) in 24 categories.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The ceremony was televised in the United States by ABC, and was produced by Bill Mechanic and Adam Shankman and directed by Hamish Hamilton.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Actors Alec Baldwin and Steve Martin hosted the show.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Martin hosted for the third time; he first presided over the 73rd ceremony held in 2001 and last hosted the 75th ceremony held in 2003, while this was Baldwin's first Oscars hosting stint.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] This was also the first telecast to have multiple hosts since the 59th ceremony held in 1987.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] On June 24, 2009, Academy president Sid Ganis announced at a press conference that, in an attempt to revitalize interest surrounding the awards, the 2010 ceremony would feature ten Best Picture nominees instead of five, a practice that had been discontinued after the 16th ceremony in 1944.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] On February 20, 2010, in a ceremony at the Beverly Wilshire Hotel in Beverly Hills, California, the Academy Awards for Technical Achievement were presented by host Elizabeth Banks.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The nominees for the 82nd Academy Awards were announced on February 2, 2010, at 5:38 a.m.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] PST (13:38 UTC) at the Samuel Goldwyn Theater in Beverly Hills, California, by Tom Sherak, president of the Academy, and actress Anne Hathaway.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] *Avatar* and *The Hurt Locker* led the nominations with nine each.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The winners were announced during the awards ceremony on March 7, 2010.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Kathryn Bigelow made history as the first female to win the Academy Award for Best Director.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] *Precious: Based on the Novel 'Push' by Sapphire* became the first film directed by a Black director to be nominated for Best Picture.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] *Up* became the second animated film to be nominated for Best Picture after 1991's *Beauty and the Beast*.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Best Adapted Screenplay winner Geoffrey Fletcher was the first African-American winner of a screenwriting Oscar.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Meryl Streep received her thirtheenth nomination for Best Actress in a Leading Role, beting Katharine Hepburn as the most nominated actress in this category.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Winners are listed first, highlighted in **boldface** and indicated with a double dagger (‡).
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The following individuals, listed in order of appearance, presented awards or performed musical numbers.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Because of the declining viewership of recent Academy Awards ceremonies, the Academy sought ideas to revamp the show while renewing interest with the nominated films.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] After the previous year's telecast, which saw a 13% increase in viewership, many within the Motion Picture Academy proposed new ways to give the awards a more populist appeal.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] AMPAS then-president Sid Ganis announced that the ceremony would feature ten Best Picture nominees, rather than traditional five.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The expansion was a throwback to the Academy's early years in the 1930s and 1940s, when eight to twelve films were nominated.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] "Having 10 Best Picture nominees is going to allow Academy voters to recognize and include some of the fantastic movies that often show up in the other Oscar categories, but have been squeezed out of the race for the top prize," Sid Ganis said in a press conference.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] "I can't wait to see what that list of ten looks like when the nominees are announced in February." Ganis also said that became difficult to get a clear winner.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] A cause of this was required a change in the voting system from first-past-the-post to alternative vote.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Choreographer Adam Shankman and Bill Mechanic were hired as producers for the ceremony.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Many of the previous year's well-received elements returned.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Five actors with a personal connection with each of the nominees presented the Best Actor and Best Actress awards.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Shankman and Mechanic announced their intention to make the running time of the telecast shorter.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Most presenters this year introduced each winner with the phrase "And the winner is ..." rather than "And the Oscar goes to..." for the first time since 1988.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The Academy gave no reason for the change to a phrase which it had once felt humiliating to the other nominees; but apparently acquiesced in Shankman and Mechanic's decision to return to the older phrase.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] David Rockwell's proscenium curtain, decorated with 100,000 Swarovski crystals, was reused as part of the stage design for this year's telecast.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Unlike most Oscar ceremonies, however, Mechanic and Shankman announced that none of the five songs nominated for Best Original Song would be performed live.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] For the first time since 2003, the field of major nominees included at least one blockbuster at the American and Canadian box offices.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Five of the nominees had grossed over $100 million before the nominations were announced.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Many critics, reporters, and entertainment industry analysts cite the AMPAS's decision to expand the roster of Best Picture nominees from five to ten films as one of the reasons for this.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Three of the ten Best Picture nominees were among the top ten releases in box office during the nominations.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] At the time of the announcement on February 2, *Avatar* was the highest-grossing film among the Best Picture nominees with $596 million in domestic box office receipts.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Other top-ten domestic box office hits nominated were *Up* with $293 million, and *The Blind Side* with $237.9 million.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Of the top 50 grossing films of the year, 46 nominations went to 13 films on the list.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Only *Avatar* (1st), *Up* (5th), *The Blind Side* (8th), *Inglourious Basterds* (25th), *District 9* (27th), *The Princess and the Frog* (32nd), *Julie & Julia* (34th), *Coraline* (42nd) and *Up in the Air* (43rd) were nominated for directing, acting, screenwriting, Best Picture or Animated Feature.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The other top-50 box office hits that earned nominations were *Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince* (2nd), *Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen* (3rd), *Star Trek* (7th) and *Sherlock Holmes* (11th).
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] On March 1, 2010, WABC-TV New York, ABC's flagship station, announced that it would likely end its services with cable television company Cablevision on March 7, 2010, the weekend of the 82nd Academy Awards.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The station was removed from Cablevision's lineup at 12:01 a.m.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Over 3.1 million viewers in the New York City viewing area, the nation's largest media market, would have been unable to watch the Oscars (and other station-related and ABC-related programming), and it was projected to cause a devastating blow to advertisers and viewership for the Oscars.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] ET, thirteen minutes after the awards ceremony began, Cablevision resumed transmission of the WABC feed.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Shortly after *Music by Prudence* director Roger Ross Williams began his speech accepting the Oscar for Best Documentary Short Subject, he was suddenly interrupted by Elinor Burkett, his co-producer.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The scene was described as the ceremony's weirdest or most awkward moment, and was compared by Williams and others to Kanye West's interruption of Taylor Swift's acceptance of the Best Female Video Award at the 2009 MTV Video Music Awards five months earlier.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Burkett, who lives in Zimbabwe where most of the film was shot, had sued Williams over the finished film, a suit that had been settled by the time of the ceremony.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] She explained to *Salon.com*, to which she was once a contributor, that the film had been her idea.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] "Roger had never even heard of Zimbabwe before I told him about this." She had been upset that Williams and HBO chose to focus on one person instead of the entire band, as the members had been led to believe.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] "I felt my role in this has been denigrated again and again, and it wasn't going to happen this time." She hustled onstage because, she claimed, Williams' mother had blocked her from going down with her cane to prevent her from sharing the stage.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] "She just ambushed me", said Williams, "I just expected her to stand there.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] I had a speech prepared." He said it was made clear by the Academy that only one person can give an acceptance speech.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] He said his mother had merely gotten up to hug him.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The show received a mixed reception from media publications.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Some media outlets were more critical of the show.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Film critic Roger Ebert criticized the opening monologue of Baldwin and Martin saying it was "surprisingly unfunny".
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] He later went on to say that there was joy that *The Hurt Locker* won, but choice of Baldwin and Martin as host was wrong.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] He also noted that having two hosts was a disadvantage.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Other media outlets received the broadcast more positively.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The American telecast on ABC drew in an average of 41.62 million people over its length, which was a 13% increase from the previous year's ceremony.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] An estimated 79.68 million total viewers watched all or part of the awards.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The show also drew higher Nielsen ratings compared to the two previous ceremonies with 24.89% of households watching over a 36.69 share.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] In addition, the program scored a higher 18-49 demo rating with a 12.71 rating over a 31.51 share among viewers in that demographic.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] It was the highest viewership for an Academy Award telecast since the 77th ceremony held in 2005.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] In July 2010, the ceremony presentation received 12 nominations at the 62nd Primetime Emmys.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The following month, the ceremony won one of those nominations for Outstanding Art Direction for Variety, Music or Nonfiction Programming (David Rockwell and Joe Celli).
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The annual *In Memoriam* tribute, produced by Chuck Workman, was presented by actress Demi Moore.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] Singer James Taylor performed The Beatles' song "In My Life" during the tribute.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] A separate tribute was held earlier in the evening for filmmaker John Hughes, presented by actors Matthew Broderick, Molly Ringwald, Judd Nelson, Ally Sheedy, Anthony Michael Hall, Macaulay Culkin and Jon Cryer.
[src:bomb-disposal/82nd-academy-awards] The 77th telecast had previously featured a special memorial to Johnny Carson presented by Chris Rock and Whoopi Goldberg.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Aberdeen Proving Ground was formed in 1917 to provide the Army with sufficient land for testing its munitions and equipment.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Around the same time, the **Edgewood Arsenal** was established on separate land, and provided the production and testing of chemical weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Edgewood Arsenal was discontinued as a separate installation in 1971 and its resources were transferred to Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The "Aberdeen area" refers to the northeastern side of APG, while the "Edgewood area" refers to the southwestern side, formerly the Edgewood Arsenal.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] A portion of Edgewood Arsenal was separated into **Fort Hoyle** in 1922, to house artillery units of the Army.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The post was incorporated back into Edgewood Arsenal in 1940.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Army's oldest active proving ground, established on October 20, 1917—six months after the U.S. entered World War I.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The planning and construction were overseen by Brigadier General Colden Ruggles, who later served as the Army's Chief of Ordnance.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Its location allowed for design and testing of ordnance materiel to take place near contemporary industrial and shipping centers.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The proving ground was created as a successor to the Sandy Hook Proving Ground, which was too small for some of the larger weapons being tested.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] At the peak of World War II, the Aberdeen Proving Ground had billeting space for 24,189 enlisted personnel and 2,348 officers.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Conant, who helped develop Lewisite at Aberdeen, went on to become the President of Harvard, and oversaw the Manhattan Project for the Office of Scientific Research and Development (OSRD).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Aberdeen was home to the Army Pulse Radiation Facility Reactor.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On September 6, 1968, this reactor was the site of a prompt critical excursion during commissioning tests.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] This accident harmed no personnel but did release enough heat to reach the melting point of the fuel in the core, at 1150 °C (2100 °F).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] This caused damage to the fuel components of the reactor, fusing the four central rings together.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] This is one of thirty-three prompt critical accidents worldwide, between 1949 and 2000.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Under the Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) program, as announced in 2005, the APG was projected to lose the Ordnance School and associated R&D facilities, with 3,862 military and 290 civilian jobs moving to Fort Lee, Virginia.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] APG would gain 451 military and 5,661 civilian jobs from Fort Monmouth, New Jersey.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] As a result, APG incurred a net-loss of 3,411 military jobs and gain of 5,371 civilian jobs.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Army Ordnance Corps Museum was previously located at APG, then moved to Fort Lee, Virginia, as a result of the 2005 Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) Act.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Although mostly civilian contractors produced conventional munitions during World War I, the United States government built federally owned plants on Aberdeen Proving Ground to manufacture toxic gas.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] These poison gas manufacturing facilities came to be known as Edgewood Arsenal, officially designated on May 4, 1918.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Edgewood Arsenal included plants to manufacture mustard gas, chloropicrin and phosgene, and separate facilities to fill artillery shells with these chemicals.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Production began in 1918, would reach 2,756 short tons (2,500 t) per month, and totaled 10,817 short tons (9,813 t) of toxic gas manufactured at Edgewood Arsenal before the November 1918 armistice.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Some of this gas was shipped overseas for use in French and British artillery shells.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Edgewood area of Aberdeen Proving Ground is approximately 13,000 acres (5,300 ha) or 20.31 square miles (52.6 km2).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Edgewood area was used for the development and testing of chemical agent munitions.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] From 1917 to the present, the Edgewood area conducted chemical research programs, manufactured chemical agents, and tested, stored, and disposed of toxic materials.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On July 1, 1971, the Edgewood Arsenal was discontinued as a separate installation, and its personnel, resources, and facilities transferred to Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The merger intended to reduce operating costs of the installations.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The land from Edgewood Arsenal is known today as the Edgewood area.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Gunpowder Meetinghouse and Presbury Meetinghouse located within the grounds of Edgewood Arsenal are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Army Chemical Corps conducted classified medical studies at Edgewood Arsenal, Maryland, intending to evaluate the impact of low-dose chemical warfare agents on military personnel, and test protective clothing and pharmaceuticals.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] About 7,000 soldiers took part in these experiments, involving exposures to more than 250 different chemicals, according to the U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] At the time, some volunteers exhibited symptoms of chemical agent exposure, but long-term follow-up was not planned as part of the DoD studies.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] During the week of July 14, 1969, personnel from Naval Applied Science Laboratory in conjunction with personnel from Limited War Laboratory conducted a defoliation test along the shoreline of Poole's Island, Aberdeen Proving Ground using Agent Orange and Agent Orange Plus foam.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Fort Hoyle was officially disestablished as a separate military post when it was reabsorbed by Edgewood Arsenal on September 10, 1940.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Other parts of APG not attached to the main installation include: the Churchville Test Area in Harford County, and the Carroll Island and Graces Quarters in Baltimore County, Maryland.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Churchville Test Area is a test track with hills that provide steep natural grades and tight turns to stress engines, drivetrains, and suspensions for army vehicles, including M1 Abrams tanks, Bradley Fighting Vehicles, and Humvees.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The eastern half of Carroll Island was used as a testing location for open air static testing of chemical weapons since the 1950s.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Simulant agents, incendiaries, decontaminating compounds, signaling and screening smokes, mustard, and herbicides were also released as well as riot control gasses.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The test sites consisted of spray grids, a wind tunnel, test grids, and small buildings.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Aberdeen Proving Ground occupies a land area of 72,500 acres (equivalent to 113.3 square miles, or 293 square kilometers).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Its northernmost point is near the mouth of the Susquehanna River, where the river enters the Chesapeake Bay, while on the south, it is bordered by the Gunpowder River.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The installation lies on two peninsulas separated by the Bush River.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The northeastern area is known as the *Aberdeen Area* and the southwestern area is called the *Edgewood Area* (formerly the *Edgewood Arsenal*).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Census Bureau, the CDP has a total area of 12.0 square miles (31.1 km2), of which 11.4 square miles (29.5 km2) is land and 0.6 square miles (1.6 km2) (5.09%) is water.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] For statistical purposes the base is delineated as a census-designated place (Aberdeen Proving Ground CDP) by the U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] As of the 2020 census, the resident population was 1,668.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] As of the census of 2000, there were 3,116 people, 805 households, and 763 families residing in the CDP.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The population density was 274.1 inhabitants per square mile (105.8/km2).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] There were 902 housing units at an average density of 79.3 per square mile (30.6/km2).
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The racial makeup of the CDP was 50.5% White, 34.6% African American, 0.6% Native American, 3.1% Asian, 1.3% Pacific Islander, 5.7% from other races, and 4.2% from two or more races; 11.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] In the CDP, the population was spread out, with 40.1% under the age of 18, 10.3% from 18 to 24, 44.9% from 25 to 44, 4.4% from 45 to 64, and 0.2% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] For every 100 females, there were 113.9 males.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 117.6 males.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The median income for a household in the CDP was $38,875, and the median income for a family was $40,306.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Males had a median income of $26,943 versus $26,194 for females.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The per capita income for the CDP was $12,808.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] About 4.2% of families and 5.6% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6.4% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Edgewood Chemical Activity (ECA) was a depot that stored chemical weapons on APG.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Elimination of the depot's chemical materials was put on an accelerated schedule following the September 11 attacks.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The depot's chemical weapons were destroyed by February 2006.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Edgewood area of the Aberdeen Proving Ground site was proposed to the Environmental Protection Agency's National Priorities List of the most serious uncontrolled or abandoned hazardous waste sites requiring long term remedial action on April 10, 1985.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The site was formally added to the National Priorities List on February 21, 1990.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Edgewood area has large areas of land and water and numerous buildings that are contaminated or suspected of contamination.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Virtually all the land areas of the site contain contaminated or potentially contaminated sites and potentially buried ordnance.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Substances disposed of in the area include significant quantities of napalm, white phosphorus, and chemical agents.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On-site surface waters include rivers, streams, and wetlands.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Edgewood area standby water supply wells in the Canal Creek area previously served approximately 3,000 people.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The Long Bar Harbor well field of the County Department of Public Works and the well field used by the Joppatowne Sanitary Subdistrict serve 35,000 people within 3 miles (4.8 km) of the site.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On-site groundwater sampling has identified perchlorate, various metals, volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and chemical warfare agent degradation products.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On-site soil contamination sampling has identified various VOCs, metals, and unexploded ordnance in surface and subsurface soil.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] On-site surface water sampling has identified various metals, pesticides, phosphorus, and VOCs.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] People who accidentally ingest or come in direct contact with contaminated groundwater, surface water, soil, or sediments may be at risk.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The area is a designated habitat for bald eagles.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Army brought charges against twelve commissioned and non-commissioned male officers for sexual assault of female trainees under their command.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] Following campaigning by PETA, the Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, and other organizations, the U.S. military announced in 2011 it was replacing its use of monkeys in the Army's nerve-agent attack training courses with human simulators and other non-animal teaching methods.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] The training drills had been carried out on vervet monkeys at Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] A Joint Land Attack Cruise Missile Defense Elevated Netted Sensor System (JLENS) broke free from its mooring station at APG on October 28, 2015.
[src:bomb-disposal/aberdeen-proving-ground] It traveled for three hours through the skies, finally crashing in a wooded area in northeastern Pennsylvania.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In 1875, he framed the Explosives Act, the first modern legislation for explosives control.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] He also pioneered many bomb disposal techniques, including remote methods for the handling and dismantling of explosives.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] His advice during the Fenian dynamite campaign of 1881–85 was officially recognised as having contributed to the saving of lives.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] After Victoria Station was bombed on 26 February 1884, he defused a bomb built with a clockwork mechanism which might have gone off at any moment.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The New York City Police Department established its first bomb squad in 1903.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Known as the "Italian Squad", its primary mission was to deal with dynamite bombs used by the Mafia to intimidate immigrant Italian merchants and residents.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] It would later be known as the "Anarchist Squad" and the "Radical Squad" for its response to radical bomb attacks in the wake of the 1919 United States anarchist bombings.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Bomb disposal became a formalized practice during World War I.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The swift mass production of munitions led to many manufacturing defects, and a large proportion of shells fired by both sides were found to be "duds".
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] These were hazardous to attacker and defender alike.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In response, the British dedicated a section of Ordnance Examiners from the Royal Army Ordnance Corps to handle the growing problem.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In 1918, the Germans developed delayed-action fuzes that would later develop into more sophisticated versions during the 1930s, as Nazi Germany began its secret course of arms development.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] These tests led to the development of UXBs (unexploded bombs), pioneered by Herbert Ruehlemann of Rheinmetall, and first employed during the Spanish Civil War of 1936–37.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Such delayed-action bombs provoked terror in the civilian population because of the uncertainty of time, and also complicated the task of disarming them.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Germans saw that unexploded bombs caused far more chaos and disruption than bombs that exploded immediately.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This caused them to increase their usage of delayed-action bombs in World War II.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Initially there were no specialized tools, training, or core knowledge available, and as Ammunition Technicians learned how to neutralize one variant of munition safely, the enemy would add or change parts to make neutralization efforts more hazardous.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This trend of cat-and-mouse extends even to the present day, and the various techniques used to disarm munitions are not publicized.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Modern EOD technicians across the world can trace their heritage to the Blitz, when the United Kingdom's cities were subjected to extensive bombing raids by Nazi Germany.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In addition to conventional air raids, unexploded bombs (UXBs) took their toll on population and morale, paralyzing vital services and communications.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Bombs fitted with delayed-action fuzes provoked fear and uncertainty in the civilian population.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The first UXBs were encountered in the autumn of 1939 before the Blitz and were for the most part easily dealt with, mostly by Royal Air Force or Air Raid Precautions personnel.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In the spring of 1940, when the Phony War ended, the British realized that they were going to need professionals in numbers to deal with the coming problem.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] 25 sections were authorized for the Royal Engineers in May 1940, another 109 in June, and 220 by August.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Organization was needed, and as the Blitz began, 25 "Bomb Disposal Companies" were created between August 1940 and January 1941.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Each company had ten sections, each section having a bomb disposal officer and 14 other ranks to assist.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Six companies were deployed in London by January 1941.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The problem of UXBs was further complicated when Royal Engineer bomb disposal personnel began to encounter munitions fitted with anti-handling devices e.g. the Luftwaffe's ZUS40 anti-removal bomb fuze of 1940.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Bomb fuzes incorporating anti-handling devices were specifically designed to kill bomb disposal personnel.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Scientists and technical staff responded by devising methods and equipment to render them safe, including the work of Eric Moxey.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The United States War Department felt the British bomb disposal experience could be a valuable asset, based on reports from U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Army, Navy, and Marine Corps observers at RAF Melksham in Wiltshire, England in 1940.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The next year, the Office of Civilian Defense (OCD) and War Department both sponsored a bomb disposal program.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] After the attack on Pearl Harbor, the British sent instructors to Aberdeen Proving Ground, where the U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Army would inaugurate a formal bomb disposal school under the Ordnance Corps.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Army Ordnance Bomb Disposal School commandant, and later served as ETO Director of Bomb Disposal under Dwight D.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In May 1941, British colleagues helped establish the Naval Mine Disposal School at the Naval Gun Factory, Washington, D.C.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Navy, under the command of Lieutenant Draper L.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Kauffman (who would go on to found the Underwater Demolition Teams – better known as UDTs or the U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Navy Frogmen), created the Naval Bomb Disposal School at University Campus, Washington, D.C.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The first US Army Bomb Disposal companies were deployed in North Africa and Sicily, but proved cumbersome and were replaced with mobile seven-man squads in 1943.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Wartime errors were rectified in 1947 when Army personnel started attending a new school at Indian Head, Maryland, under U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] That same year, the forerunner of the EOD Technology Center, the USN Bureau of Naval Weapons, charged with research, development, test, and evaluation of EOD tools, tactics and procedures, was born.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Ammunition Technicians of the Royal Logistic Corps (RLC, formerly RAOC) became highly experienced in bomb disposal, after many years of dealing with bombs planted by the Provisional Irish Republican Army (PIRA) and other groups.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The bombs employed by the PIRA ranged from simple pipe bombs to sophisticated victim-triggered devices and infrared switches.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The roadside bomb was in use by PIRA from the early 1970s onwards, evolving over time with different types of explosives and triggers.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Improvised mortars were also developed by the IRA, usually placed in static vehicles, with self-destruct mechanisms.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] During the 38-year campaign in Northern Ireland, 23 British ATO bomb disposal specialists were killed in action.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] A specialist Army unit, 321 EOD Unit (later 321 EOD Company, and now 321 EOD & Search Squadron RLC part of 11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Regiment RLC), was deployed to tackle increased IRA violence and willingness to use bombs against both economic and military targets.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] All units in Northern Ireland had a callsign to be used over the radios.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] 321 Company, a newly formed unit, didn't have such a callsign, so a young signaller was sent to the OC of 321 Coy.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The OC, having lost two technicians that morning, decided on "Phoenix".
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This was misheard as "Felix" by the signaller and was never changed.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The other possible reason is that the callsign for RAOC was "Rickshaw"; however, the 321 EOD felt it needed its own callsign, hence the deliberate choice of "Felix the Cat with nine lives".
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] 321 Coy RAOC (now 321 EOD & Search Sqn RLC) is the most decorated unit (in peacetime) in the British Army with over 200 gallantry awards, notably for acts of great bravery during Operation Banner (1969–2007) in Northern Ireland.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The US Forces commanders requested British Ammunition Technicians of 11 EOD & Search Regiment RLC to operate in support of the US Marine Corps in clearing the Iraqi oilfields of booby traps.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They were among the first British service personnel sent into Iraq in 2003 before the ground invasion.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The eruption of low intensity conflicts and terrorism waves at the beginning of the 21st century caused further development in the techniques and methods of bomb disposal.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD operators and technicians had to adapt to rapidly evolving methods of constructing improvised explosive devices ranging from shrapnel-filled explosive belts to 100 kg bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Since improvised explosives are generally unreliable and very unstable they pose great risk to the public and especially to the EOD Operator trying to render them safe.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Therefore, new methods like greater reliance on remote techniques such as advanced remotely operated vehicles similar to the British Wheelbarrow or armored bulldozers evolved.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Many nations have developed their own versions such as the D7 MCAP and the armored D9R.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Besides large mine-clearing vehicles such as the Trojan, the British Army also uses small remote controlled vehicles such as the Dragon Runner and the Chevette.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] During the al-Aqsa Intifada, Israeli EOD forces disarmed and detonated thousands of explosive charges, lab bombs and explosive ammunition (such as rockets).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Two Israeli EOD teams gained high reputation for leading the efforts in that area: the Army's Israeli Engineering Corps' Sayeret Yahalom and the Israeli Border Guard Gaza-area EOD team.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In the Iraq War, the Multi-National Force – Iraq faced many bombs on travel routes.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Such charges can easily destroy light vehicles such as the Humvee, and large ones can destroy main battle tanks.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Such charges caused many casualties and, along with car bombs and suicide bombers, were a major cause of casualties in Iraq.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In Spain's autonomous Basque Country, where bombings by Basque separatist groups were common during the 1980s and 1990s, there are three corps in charge of bomb disposal: Policia Nacional, Guardia Civil, and Ertzaintza.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Ertzaintza handle general civilian threats, while the Policia Nacional and Guardia Civil maintain capabilities mainly to defend their own assets and personnel.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In other parts of the country, the Guardia Civil and Policia Nacional develop their tasks within their own abilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD continues to face multiple challenges throughout the 21st century as the proliferation of explosive ordnance continues worldwide.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Russo-Ukraine War, Gaza - Israel Conflict, and 2026 Iran War example conflicts where the demand for trained and capable EOD forces are required to protect forces, civilians, personnel, and equipment.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD is challenged to rapidly adapt to new conventional ordnance threats and new improvised techniques, all while maintaining historic competencies.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Additionally, the scale and scope of these challenges tends to overwhelm available EOD capacity, resulting in long-term remediation challenges.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In the United States, Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) is a specialized technical area in military and law enforcement.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Each military service maintains its own EOD force, with the US Navy as the executive agent for the US military's EOD program.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD qualification is earned after successful graduation from the US Naval School - Explosive Ordnance Disposal (NAVSCOLEOD).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Upon graduation of NAVSCOLEOD, US military members earn a military occupational skill (MOS) code associated with their branch of service.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Each service often requires additional certifications, skills, and training before individuals are full approve to operate.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Each service is responsible for EOD response on their respective installations and often provide support to local areas, as required.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] US EOD covers both on- and off-base calls in the US unless there is a local PSBT or "Public Safety Bomb Technician" who can handle the bomb; ordnance should only be handled by the EOD experts.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Also called a "Hazardous Devices Technician", PSBTs are usually members of a police department, although teams are also formed by fire departments or emergency management agencies.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] To be certified, a PSBT must attend the FBI Hazardous Devices School at Redstone Arsenal, Alabama which is modeled on the International IEDD Training school at The Army School of Ammunition, known as the Felix Centre.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This school helps them to become knowledgeable in the detection, diagnosis, and disposal of hazardous devices.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They are further trained to collect evidence in hazardous devices, and present expert-witness testimony in court on bombing cases.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In the United Kingdom, EOD operators are held within all three services.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Each service has differing responsibilities for UXO, however they will often work closely on operations.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Ammunition Technical Officers and Ammunition Technicians of the Royal Logistic Corps deal with many aspects of EOD, including conventional munitions and homemade bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They are also trained in chemical, biological, incendiary, radiological ("dirty bombs"), and nuclear weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They provide support to VIPs, help civilian authorities with bomb problems, teach personnel from all three services about bomb safety, and a variety of other tasks.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Royal Engineers of 33 Engineer Regiment (EOD) provide EOD expertise for air dropped munitions in peacetime and conventional munitions on operations, as well as battle area clearance and High Risk Search in support of improvised explosive device disposal.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They also provide expertise in Advanced IEDD and in the investigation of accidents and incidents involving ammunition and explosives, where they are seen as Subject Matter Experts (SMEs).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Weapons Intelligence is supplied by Royal Military Police, Intelligence Corps and Ammunition Technical Personnel who tap into the Combined Explosive Exploitation Cell (CEXC) units of the US.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] All prospective Ammunition Technicians attend a grueling course of instruction at The Army School of Ammunition and the Felix Centre, United Kingdom.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The time frame for an RLC Ammunition Technician to complete all necessary courses prior to finally being placed on an EOD team is around 36 months.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Whereas the Engineer EOD training period although shorter in total is spread over a number of years and interspersed with operational experience, RE personnel may be posted to core trades such as carpentry or bridge building within their time as engineers.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Royal Navy clearance divers also deploy teams both in the UK and on operations working on both IEDD (Improvised Explosive Device Disposal) teams as well as the disposal of conventional munitions.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Royal Navy personnel spend their entire service working with and around explosives, and associated sciences.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] As such are given responsibilities relevant to their roles when it comes to conventional weapons.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] NATO Alliance countries qualify their EOD forces at different levels.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Due to the potential discrepancy in capability, NATO defines its EOD capabilities at different levels to improve interoperability and standardization.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Underwater specializations for all the above listed capabilities exist as well with additional dive training and certifications.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In addition to neutralizing munitions or bombs, conducting training and presenting evidence, EOD Technicians and Engineers also respond to other problems.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD Technicians help dispose old or unstable explosives, such as ones used in quarrying, mining, or old/unstable fireworks and ammunition.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They also assist specialist police units, raid and entry teams with boobytrap detection and avoidance, and they help in conducting post-blast investigations.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The EOD technician's training and experience with bombs make them an integral part of any bombing investigation.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Another part of an EOD technician's job involves supporting the government intelligence units.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This involves searching all places that the high ranking government officers or other protected dignitaries travel, stay or visit.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Generally, EOD *render-safe procedures* (RSP) are a type of tradecraft protected from public dissemination in order to limit access and knowledge, depriving the enemy of specific technical procedures used to render safe ordnance or an improvised device.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Another reason for keeping tradecraft secret is to hinder the development of new anti-handling devices by their opponents: if the enemy has thorough knowledge of specific EOD techniques, it can develop fuze designs which are more resistant to existing render-safe procedures.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Many techniques exist for the making safe of a bomb or munition.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Selection of a technique depends on several variables.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The greatest variable is the proximity of the munition or device to people or critical facilities.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Explosives in remote localities are handled very differently from those in densely populated areas.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The role of modern bomb disposal operators is to accomplish their task as remotely as possible.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Actually laying hands on a bomb is only done in an extremely life-threatening situation, where the hazards to people and critical structures cannot be reduced.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] EOD technicians have many tools for remote operations, one of which is the RCV, or remote-control vehicle, also known as the "Wheelbarrow".
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Outfitted with cameras, microphones, and sensors for chemical, biological, or nuclear agents, the Wheelbarrow can help the technician get an excellent idea of what the munition or device is.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Many of these robots even have hand-like manipulators in case a door needs to be opened, or a munition or bomb requires handling or moving.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The first ever Wheelbarrow was conceived by Major 'Pat' Wilson Patterson RAOC and his team at the Bomb Disposal School, CAD Kineton in 1972 and used by ammunition technicians in the battle against Provisional Irish Republican Army bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Also of great use are items that allow ammunition technicians to remotely diagnose the innards of a munition or bomb.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] These include devices similar to the X-ray used by medical personnel, and high-performance sensors that can detect and help interpret sounds, odors, or even images from within the munition or bomb.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Once the technicians determine what the munition or device is, and what state it is in, they will formulate a procedure to disarm it.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This may include things as simple as replacing safety features, or as difficult as using high-powered explosive-actuated devices to shear, jam, bind, or remove parts of the item's firing train.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Preferably, this will be accomplished remotely, but there are still circumstances when a robot won't do and technicians must put themself at risk by personally going near the bomb.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Technicians will don specialized protective suits, using flame and fragmentation-resistant material similar to bulletproof vests.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Some suits have advanced features such as internal cooling, amplified hearing, and communications back to the control area.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This suit is designed to increase the odds of survival for technicians should munitions or bombs detonate while they are near it.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Rarely, the specifics of a munition or bomb will allow the technician to first remove it from the area.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] In these cases, a containment vessel is used.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Using remote methods, the technician places the item in the container and retires to a remote area to complete the defusion.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] This procedure, called a Render Safe Procedure, can take a great deal of time.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Because of the construction of devices, a waiting period must be taken to ensure that whatever render-safe method was used worked as intended.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Another technique is Trepanation, in which a bore is cut into the sidewall of a bomb and the explosive contents are extracted through a combination of steam and acid bath liquefaction of bomb contents.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] German EOD experts were notified and attended the scene.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Whilst residents living nearby were being evacuated and the EOD personnel were preparing to disarm the bomb, it detonated, killing three of them and injuring 6 others.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The dead and injured each had over 20 years of hands-on experience, and had previously rendered safe between 600 and 700 unexploded bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The bomb which killed and injured the EOD personnel was of a particularly dangerous type because it was fitted with a delayed-action chemical fuze, which had become highly unstable after over 65 years under ground.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] A bomb disposal vehicle is a vehicle used by bomb disposal squads to transport equipment and bomb disposal robots, or to store bombs for later disposal.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They are often vans or trucks, typically with at least one bomb containment chamber installed in the rear of the vehicle, and ramps to allow bomb disposal robots to access the vehicle.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Bomb disposal vehicles are generally not explosive-resistant and are only used for transporting explosives for disposal, not actively disposing of them.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Portable X-ray systems are used to radiograph the bomb before intervention.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The purpose is for example to determine if a chemical charge is present or to check the status of the detonator.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] High steel thickness requires high energy and high power sources.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Projected water disruptors use a water-projectile shaped charge to destroy bombs, blasting the device apart and severing any detonating connections faster than any fuse or anti-tampering device on the bomb can react.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] One example is the BootBanger, deployed under the rear compartment of cars suspected to be carrying bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Projected water disruptors can be directional, such as the BootBanger; or omni-directional, an example being the Bottler.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Pigstick is the British Army's term for a waterjet disruptor, often mounted on the Wheelbarrow remotely operated vehicle to counter IRA bombs in the 1970s.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The name Pigstick was the next available at the time from the UK Ministry of Defence's list of names for classified equipment and projects.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Pigstick fires a jet of water driven by a propellant charge to disrupt the circuitry of a bomb and disable it with a low risk of detonation.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The modern pigstick is reliable and can be fired many times with minimal maintenance.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] It is 485 millimetres (19.1 in) long and weighs 2.95 kilograms (6.5 lb).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] It is made of hardened steel, and can be mounted on a remotely operated vehicle (ROV).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] These factors make it an effective way to render IEDs safe.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] It is not a panacea, however: it cannot deal with IEDs packed in hard containers such as industrial gas bottles or beer kegs, and other disruptors have been designed to deal with those and a range of different situations, including car bombs.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The device was developed by the scientists Mike Barker MBE and Peter Hubbard OBE at RARDE Fort Halstead in late 1971 working under great pressure over several weeks after an ATO died in Northern Ireland attempting to render safe the first IED in the theatre to contain anti-handling devices.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] They started with a prototype piece of equipment designed to disrupt limpet mines attached to a ship's hull and, through many trials and errors, developed a disruptor capable of dealing with the crop of IEDs with anti-handling devices prevalent at the time.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Barker used the device operationally for the first time in Northern Ireland during a visit there to demonstrate their prototype to George Styles and his team.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Pigstick prototype was re-engineered by a member of Hubbard's team, Bob White MBE, down from its original 20 kg to its current 2.95 kg form but its internal ballistic design remained true to the original.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The ZEUS-HLONS was developed for surface land mines and unexploded ordnance (UXO) neutralization by the U.S.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Naval Explosive Ordnance Disposal Technology Division (NAVEODTECHDIV).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] It uses a moderate-power commercial solid state laser (SSL) and beam control system, integrated onto a Humvee (HMMWV), to clear surface mines, improvised bombs, or unexploded ordnance (UXO) from supply routes and minefields.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] There are a wide range of containment chambers available.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The simplest are sometimes danger suppression vessels that merely contain some of the fragments generated by the explosion.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The other end of the spectrum features top-of-the-line gas-tight chambers that can withstand multiple shots while remaining able to contain chemical, biological, or radioactive agents.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Containment chambers of all types may be fitted onto towed trailers, or specialised EOD vehicles.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] There is a long history of IEDD within the UK and protection for this role has evolved over the years.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] Starting with the Mk1 in 1969, in response to the Maoist Terrorist threat in Hong Kong, through to the Mk 2 in 1974, in response to the IRA threat in Northern Ireland (NI), with further developments of the Mk3 in 1980 to include a new helmet.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The Mk4 EOD Suit, introduced into service in 1993, combines fragmentation and blast protection that is prioritised over the most vulnerable parts of the body (head, face and torso).
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The current system, MKV/VI, was introduced in 2004, and was a combined MOD/NP Aerospace project.
[src:bomb-disposal/bomb-disposal] The only part of the body that has no protection at all is the hands.
